2266/// This class provides transaction based operation on the IR.
2267/// Every change made through this class is recorded in the internal state and
2268/// can be undone (rollback) until commit is called.
2269class TypePromotionTransaction {
2270 /// This represents the common interface of the individual transaction.
2271 /// Each class implements the logic for doing one specific modification on
2272 /// the IR via the TypePromotionTransaction.
2273 class TypePromotionAction {
2274 protected:
2275 /// The Instruction modified.
2276 Instruction *Inst;
2277
2278 public:
2279 /// Constructor of the action.
2280 /// The constructor performs the related action on the IR.
2281 TypePromotionAction(Instruction *Inst) : Inst(Inst) {}
2282
2283 virtual ~TypePromotionAction() = default;
2284
2285 /// Undo the modification done by this action.
2286 /// When this method is called, the IR must be in the same state as it was
2287 /// before this action was applied.
2288 /// \pre Undoing the action works if and only if the IR is in the exact same
2289 /// state as it was directly after this action was applied.
2290 virtual void undo() = 0;
2291
2292 /// Advocate every change made by this action.
2293 /// When the results on the IR of the action are to be kept, it is important
2294 /// to call this function, otherwise hidden information may be kept forever.
2295 virtual void commit() {
2296 // Nothing to be done, this action is not doing anything.
2297 }
2298 };
2299
2300 /// Utility to remember the position of an instruction.
2301 class InsertionHandler {
2302 /// Position of an instruction.
2303 /// Either an instruction:
2304 /// - Is the first in a basic block: BB is used.
2305 /// - Has a previous instruction: PrevInst is used.
2306 union {
2307 Instruction *PrevInst;
2308 BasicBlock *BB;
2309 } Point;
2310
2311 /// Remember whether or not the instruction had a previous instruction.
2312 bool HasPrevInstruction;
2313
2314 public:
2315 /// Record the position of \p Inst.
2316 InsertionHandler(Instruction *Inst) {
2317 BasicBlock::iterator It = Inst->getIterator();
2318 HasPrevInstruction = (It != (Inst->getParent()->begin()));
2319 if (HasPrevInstruction)
2320 Point.PrevInst = &*--It;
2321 else
2322 Point.BB = Inst->getParent();
2323 }
2324
2325 /// Insert \p Inst at the recorded position.
2326 void insert(Instruction *Inst) {
2327 if (HasPrevInstruction) {
2328 if (Inst->getParent())
2329 Inst->removeFromParent();
2330 Inst->insertAfter(Point.PrevInst);
2331 } else {
2332 Instruction *Position = &*Point.BB->getFirstInsertionPt();
2333 if (Inst->getParent())
2334 Inst->moveBefore(Position);
2335 else
2336 Inst->insertBefore(Position);
2337 }
2338 }
2339 };
2340
2341 /// Move an instruction before another.
2342 class InstructionMoveBefore : public TypePromotionAction {
2343 /// Original position of the instruction.
2344 InsertionHandler Position;
2345
2346 public:
2347 /// Move \p Inst before \p Before.
2348 InstructionMoveBefore(Instruction *Inst, Instruction *Before)
2349 : TypePromotionAction(Inst), Position(Inst) {
2350 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Do: move: " << *Inst << "\nbefore: " << *Before
2351 << "\n");
2352 Inst->moveBefore(Before);
2353 }
2354
2355 /// Move the instruction back to its original position.
2356 void undo() override {
2357 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Undo: moveBefore: " << *Inst << "\n");
2358 Position.insert(Inst);
2359 }
2360 };
2361
2362 /// Set the operand of an instruction with a new value.
2363 class OperandSetter : public TypePromotionAction {
2364 /// Original operand of the instruction.
2365 Value *Origin;
2366
2367 /// Index of the modified instruction.
2368 unsigned Idx;
2369
2370 public:
2371 /// Set \p Idx operand of \p Inst with \p NewVal.
2372 OperandSetter(Instruction *Inst, unsigned Idx, Value *NewVal)
2373 : TypePromotionAction(Inst), Idx(Idx) {
2374 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Do: setOperand: " << Idx << "\n"
2375 << "for:" << *Inst << "\n"
2376 << "with:" << *NewVal << "\n");
2377 Origin = Inst->getOperand(Idx);
2378 Inst->setOperand(Idx, NewVal);
2379 }
2380
2381 /// Restore the original value of the instruction.
2382 void undo() override {
2383 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Undo: setOperand:" << Idx << "\n"
2384 << "for: " << *Inst << "\n"
2385 << "with: " << *Origin << "\n");
2386 Inst->setOperand(Idx, Origin);
2387 }
2388 };
2389
2390 /// Hide the operands of an instruction.
2391 /// Do as if this instruction was not using any of its operands.
2392 class OperandsHider : public TypePromotionAction {
2393 /// The list of original operands.
2394 SmallVector<Value *, 4> OriginalValues;
2395
2396 public:
2397 /// Remove \p Inst from the uses of the operands of \p Inst.
2398 OperandsHider(Instruction *Inst) : TypePromotionAction(Inst) {
2399 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Do: OperandsHider: " << *Inst << "\n");
2400 unsigned NumOpnds = Inst->getNumOperands();
2401 OriginalValues.reserve(NumOpnds);
2402 for (unsigned It = 0; It < NumOpnds; ++It) {
2403 // Save the current operand.
2404 Value *Val = Inst->getOperand(It);
2405 OriginalValues.push_back(Val);
2406 // Set a dummy one.
2407 // We could use OperandSetter here, but that would imply an overhead
2408 // that we are not willing to pay.
2409 Inst->setOperand(It, UndefValue::get(Val->getType()));
2410 }
2411 }
2412
2413 /// Restore the original list of uses.
2414 void undo() override {
2415 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Undo: OperandsHider: " << *Inst << "\n");
2416 for (unsigned It = 0, EndIt = OriginalValues.size(); It != EndIt; ++It)
2417 Inst->setOperand(It, OriginalValues[It]);
2418 }
2419 };
2420
2421 /// Build a truncate instruction.
2422 class TruncBuilder : public TypePromotionAction {
2423 Value *Val;
2424
2425 public:
2426 /// Build a truncate instruction of \p Opnd producing a \p Ty
2427 /// result.
2428 /// trunc Opnd to Ty.
2429 TruncBuilder(Instruction *Opnd, Type *Ty) : TypePromotionAction(Opnd) {
2430 IRBuilder<> Builder(Opnd);
2431 Val = Builder.CreateTrunc(Opnd, Ty, "promoted");
2432 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Do: TruncBuilder: " << *Val << "\n");
2433 }
2434
2435 /// Get the built value.
2436 Value *getBuiltValue() { return Val; }
2437
2438 /// Remove the built instruction.
2439 void undo() override {
2440 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Undo: TruncBuilder: " << *Val << "\n");
2441 if (Instruction *IVal = dyn_cast<Instruction>(Val))
2442 IVal->eraseFromParent();
2443 }
2444 };
2445
2446 /// Build a sign extension instruction.
2447 class SExtBuilder : public TypePromotionAction {
2448 Value *Val;
2449
2450 public:
2451 /// Build a sign extension instruction of \p Opnd producing a \p Ty
2452 /// result.
2453 /// sext Opnd to Ty.
2454 SExtBuilder(Instruction *InsertPt, Value *Opnd, Type *Ty)
2455 : TypePromotionAction(InsertPt) {
2456 IRBuilder<> Builder(InsertPt);
2457 Val = Builder.CreateSExt(Opnd, Ty, "promoted");
2458 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Do: SExtBuilder: " << *Val << "\n");
2459 }
2460
2461 /// Get the built value.
2462 Value *getBuiltValue() { return Val; }
2463
2464 /// Remove the built instruction.
2465 void undo() override {
2466 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Undo: SExtBuilder: " << *Val << "\n");
2467 if (Instruction *IVal = dyn_cast<Instruction>(Val))
2468 IVal->eraseFromParent();
2469 }
2470 };
2471
2472 /// Build a zero extension instruction.
2473 class ZExtBuilder : public TypePromotionAction {
2474 Value *Val;
2475
2476 public:
2477 /// Build a zero extension instruction of \p Opnd producing a \p Ty
2478 /// result.
2479 /// zext Opnd to Ty.
2480 ZExtBuilder(Instruction *InsertPt, Value *Opnd, Type *Ty)
2481 : TypePromotionAction(InsertPt) {
2482 IRBuilder<> Builder(InsertPt);
2483 Val = Builder.CreateZExt(Opnd, Ty, "promoted");
2484 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Do: ZExtBuilder: " << *Val << "\n");
2485 }
2486
2487 /// Get the built value.
2488 Value *getBuiltValue() { return Val; }
2489
2490 /// Remove the built instruction.
2491 void undo() override {
2492 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Undo: ZExtBuilder: " << *Val << "\n");
2493 if (Instruction *IVal = dyn_cast<Instruction>(Val))
2494 IVal->eraseFromParent();
2495 }
2496 };
2497
2498 /// Mutate an instruction to another type.
2499 class TypeMutator : public TypePromotionAction {
2500 /// Record the original type.
2501 Type *OrigTy;
2502
2503 public:
2504 /// Mutate the type of \p Inst into \p NewTy.
2505 TypeMutator(Instruction *Inst, Type *NewTy)
2506 : TypePromotionAction(Inst), OrigTy(Inst->getType()) {
2507 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Do: MutateType: " << *Inst << " with " << *NewTy
2508 << "\n");
2509 Inst->mutateType(NewTy);
2510 }
2511
2512 /// Mutate the instruction back to its original type.
2513 void undo() override {
2514 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Undo: MutateType: " << *Inst << " with " << *OrigTy
2515 << "\n");
2516 Inst->mutateType(OrigTy);
2517 }
2518 };
2519
2520 /// Replace the uses of an instruction by another instruction.
2521 class UsesReplacer : public TypePromotionAction {
2522 /// Helper structure to keep track of the replaced uses.
2523 struct InstructionAndIdx {
2524 /// The instruction using the instruction.
2525 Instruction *Inst;
2526
2527 /// The index where this instruction is used for Inst.
2528 unsigned Idx;
2529
2530 InstructionAndIdx(Instruction *Inst, unsigned Idx)
2531 : Inst(Inst), Idx(Idx) {}
2532 };
2533
2534 /// Keep track of the original uses (pair Instruction, Index).
2535 SmallVector<InstructionAndIdx, 4> OriginalUses;
2536 /// Keep track of the debug users.
2537 SmallVector<DbgValueInst *, 1> DbgValues;
2538
2539 using use_iterator = SmallVectorImpl<InstructionAndIdx>::iterator;
2540
2541 public:
2542 /// Replace all the use of \p Inst by \p New.
2543 UsesReplacer(Instruction *Inst, Value *New) : TypePromotionAction(Inst) {
2544 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Do: UsersReplacer: " << *Inst << " with " << *New
2545 << "\n");
2546 // Record the original uses.
2547 for (Use &U : Inst->uses()) {
2548 Instruction *UserI = cast<Instruction>(U.getUser());
2549 OriginalUses.push_back(InstructionAndIdx(UserI, U.getOperandNo()));
2550 }
2551 // Record the debug uses separately. They are not in the instruction's
2552 // use list, but they are replaced by RAUW.
2553 findDbgValues(DbgValues, Inst);
2554
2555 // Now, we can replace the uses.
2556 Inst->replaceAllUsesWith(New);
2557 }
2558
2559 /// Reassign the original uses of Inst to Inst.
2560 void undo() override {
2561 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Undo: UsersReplacer: " << *Inst << "\n");
2562 for (use_iterator UseIt = OriginalUses.begin(),
2563 EndIt = OriginalUses.end();
2564 UseIt != EndIt; ++UseIt) {
2565 UseIt->Inst->setOperand(UseIt->Idx, Inst);
2566 }
2567 // RAUW has replaced all original uses with references to the new value,
2568 // including the debug uses. Since we are undoing the replacements,
2569 // the original debug uses must also be reinstated to maintain the
2570 // correctness and utility of debug value instructions.
2571 for (auto *DVI: DbgValues) {
2572 LLVMContext &Ctx = Inst->getType()->getContext();
2573 auto *MV = MetadataAsValue::get(Ctx, ValueAsMetadata::get(Inst));
2574 DVI->setOperand(0, MV);
2575 }
2576 }
2577 };
2578
2579 /// Remove an instruction from the IR.
2580 class InstructionRemover : public TypePromotionAction {
2581 /// Original position of the instruction.
2582 InsertionHandler Inserter;
2583
2584 /// Helper structure to hide all the link to the instruction. In other
2585 /// words, this helps to do as if the instruction was removed.
2586 OperandsHider Hider;
2587
2588 /// Keep track of the uses replaced, if any.
2589 UsesReplacer *Replacer = nullptr;
2590
2591 /// Keep track of instructions removed.
2592 SetOfInstrs &RemovedInsts;
2593
2594 public:
2595 /// Remove all reference of \p Inst and optionally replace all its
2596 /// uses with New.
2597 /// \p RemovedInsts Keep track of the instructions removed by this Action.
2598 /// \pre If !Inst->use_empty(), then New != nullptr
2599 InstructionRemover(Instruction *Inst, SetOfInstrs &RemovedInsts,
2600 Value *New = nullptr)
2601 : TypePromotionAction(Inst), Inserter(Inst), Hider(Inst),
2602 RemovedInsts(RemovedInsts) {
2603 if (New)
2604 Replacer = new UsesReplacer(Inst, New);
2605 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Do: InstructionRemover: " << *Inst << "\n");
2606 RemovedInsts.insert(Inst);
2607 /// The instructions removed here will be freed after completing
2608 /// optimizeBlock() for all blocks as we need to keep track of the
2609 /// removed instructions during promotion.
2610 Inst->removeFromParent();
2611 }
2612
2613 ~InstructionRemover() override { delete Replacer; }
2614
2615 /// Resurrect the instruction and reassign it to the proper uses if
2616 /// new value was provided when build this action.
2617 void undo() override {
2618 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Undo: InstructionRemover: " << *Inst << "\n");
2619 Inserter.insert(Inst);
2620 if (Replacer)
2621 Replacer->undo();
2622 Hider.undo();
2623 RemovedInsts.erase(Inst);
2624 }
2625 };
2626
2627public:
2628 /// Restoration point.
2629 /// The restoration point is a pointer to an action instead of an iterator
2630 /// because the iterator may be invalidated but not the pointer.
2631 using ConstRestorationPt = const TypePromotionAction *;
2632
2633 TypePromotionTransaction(SetOfInstrs &RemovedInsts)
2634 : RemovedInsts(RemovedInsts) {}
2635
2636 /// Advocate every changes made in that transaction.
2637 void commit();
2638
2639 /// Undo all the changes made after the given point.
2640 void rollback(ConstRestorationPt Point);
2641
2642 /// Get the current restoration point.
2643 ConstRestorationPt getRestorationPoint() const;
2644
2645 /// \name API for IR modification with state keeping to support rollback.
2646 /// @{
2647 /// Same as Instruction::setOperand.
2648 void setOperand(Instruction *Inst, unsigned Idx, Value *NewVal);
2649
2650 /// Same as Instruction::eraseFromParent.
2651 void eraseInstruction(Instruction *Inst, Value *NewVal = nullptr);
2652
2653 /// Same as Value::replaceAllUsesWith.
2654 void replaceAllUsesWith(Instruction *Inst, Value *New);
2655
2656 /// Same as Value::mutateType.
2657 void mutateType(Instruction *Inst, Type *NewTy);
2658
2659 /// Same as IRBuilder::createTrunc.
2660 Value *createTrunc(Instruction *Opnd, Type *Ty);
2661
2662 /// Same as IRBuilder::createSExt.
2663 Value *createSExt(Instruction *Inst, Value *Opnd, Type *Ty);
2664
2665 /// Same as IRBuilder::createZExt.
2666 Value *createZExt(Instruction *Inst, Value *Opnd, Type *Ty);
2667
2668 /// Same as Instruction::moveBefore.
2669 void moveBefore(Instruction *Inst, Instruction *Before);
2670 /// @}
2671
2672private:
2673 /// The ordered list of actions made so far.
2674 SmallVector<std::unique_ptr<TypePromotionAction>, 16> Actions;
2675
2676 using CommitPt = SmallVectorImpl<std::unique_ptr<TypePromotionAction>>::iterator;
2677
2678 SetOfInstrs &RemovedInsts;
2679};
2680
2681} // end anonymous namespace
2682
2683void TypePromotionTransaction::setOperand(Instruction *Inst, unsigned Idx,
2684 Value *NewVal) {
2685 Actions.push_back(llvm::make_unique<TypePromotionTransaction::OperandSetter>(
2686 Inst, Idx, NewVal));
2687}
2688
2689void TypePromotionTransaction::eraseInstruction(Instruction *Inst,
2690 Value *NewVal) {
2691 Actions.push_back(
2692 llvm::make_unique<TypePromotionTransaction::InstructionRemover>(
2693 Inst, RemovedInsts, NewVal));
2694}
2695
2696void TypePromotionTransaction::replaceAllUsesWith(Instruction *Inst,
2697 Value *New) {
2698 Actions.push_back(
2699 llvm::make_unique<TypePromotionTransaction::UsesReplacer>(Inst, New));
2700}
2701
2702void TypePromotionTransaction::mutateType(Instruction *Inst, Type *NewTy) {
2703 Actions.push_back(
2704 llvm::make_unique<TypePromotionTransaction::TypeMutator>(Inst, NewTy));
2705}
2706
2707Value *TypePromotionTransaction::createTrunc(Instruction *Opnd,
2708 Type *Ty) {
2709 std::unique_ptr<TruncBuilder> Ptr(new TruncBuilder(Opnd, Ty));
2710 Value *Val = Ptr->getBuiltValue();
2711 Actions.push_back(std::move(Ptr));
2712 return Val;
2713}
2714
2715Value *TypePromotionTransaction::createSExt(Instruction *Inst,
2716 Value *Opnd, Type *Ty) {
2717 std::unique_ptr<SExtBuilder> Ptr(new SExtBuilder(Inst, Opnd, Ty));
2718 Value *Val = Ptr->getBuiltValue();
2719 Actions.push_back(std::move(Ptr));
2720 return Val;
2721}
2722
2723Value *TypePromotionTransaction::createZExt(Instruction *Inst,
2724 Value *Opnd, Type *Ty) {
2725 std::unique_ptr<ZExtBuilder> Ptr(new ZExtBuilder(Inst, Opnd, Ty));
2726 Value *Val = Ptr->getBuiltValue();
2727 Actions.push_back(std::move(Ptr));
2728 return Val;
2729}
2730
2731void TypePromotionTransaction::moveBefore(Instruction *Inst,
2732 Instruction *Before) {
2733 Actions.push_back(
2734 llvm::make_unique<TypePromotionTransaction::InstructionMoveBefore>(
2735 Inst, Before));
2736}
2737
2738TypePromotionTransaction::ConstRestorationPt
2739TypePromotionTransaction::getRestorationPoint() const {
2740 return !Actions.empty() ? Actions.back().get() : nullptr;
2741}
2742
2743void TypePromotionTransaction::commit() {
2744 for (CommitPt It = Actions.begin(), EndIt = Actions.end(); It != EndIt;
2745 ++It)
2746 (*It)->commit();
2747 Actions.clear();
2748}
2749
2750void TypePromotionTransaction::rollback(
2751 TypePromotionTransaction::ConstRestorationPt Point) {
2752 while (!Actions.empty() && Point != Actions.back().get()) {
2753 std::unique_ptr<TypePromotionAction> Curr = Actions.pop_back_val();
2754 Curr->undo();
2755 }
2756}

2760/// A helper class for matching addressing modes.
2761///
2762/// This encapsulates the logic for matching the target-legal addressing modes.
2763class AddressingModeMatcher {
2764 SmallVectorImpl<Instruction*> &AddrModeInsts;
2765 const TargetLowering &TLI;
2766 const TargetRegisterInfo &TRI;
2767 const DataLayout &DL;
2768
2769 /// AccessTy/MemoryInst - This is the type for the access (e.g. double) and
2770 /// the memory instruction that we're computing this address for.
2771 Type *AccessTy;
2772 unsigned AddrSpace;
2773 Instruction *MemoryInst;
2774
2775 /// This is the addressing mode that we're building up. This is
2776 /// part of the return value of this addressing mode matching stuff.
2777 ExtAddrMode &AddrMode;
2778
2779 /// The instructions inserted by other CodeGenPrepare optimizations.
2780 const SetOfInstrs &InsertedInsts;
2781
2782 /// A map from the instructions to their type before promotion.
2783 InstrToOrigTy &PromotedInsts;
2784
2785 /// The ongoing transaction where every action should be registered.
2786 TypePromotionTransaction &TPT;
2787
2788 // A GEP which has too large offset to be folded into the addressing mode.
2789 std::pair<AssertingVH<GetElementPtrInst>, int64_t> &LargeOffsetGEP;
2790
2791 /// This is set to true when we should not do profitability checks.
2792 /// When true, IsProfitableToFoldIntoAddressingMode always returns true.
2793 bool IgnoreProfitability;
2794
2795 AddressingModeMatcher(
2796 SmallVectorImpl<Instruction *> &AMI, const TargetLowering &TLI,
2797 const TargetRegisterInfo &TRI, Type *AT, unsigned AS, Instruction *MI,
2798 ExtAddrMode &AM, const SetOfInstrs &InsertedInsts,
2799 InstrToOrigTy &PromotedInsts, TypePromotionTransaction &TPT,
2800 std::pair<AssertingVH<GetElementPtrInst>, int64_t> &LargeOffsetGEP)
2801 : AddrModeInsts(AMI), TLI(TLI), TRI(TRI),
2802 DL(MI->getModule()->getDataLayout()), AccessTy(AT), AddrSpace(AS),
2803 MemoryInst(MI), AddrMode(AM), InsertedInsts(InsertedInsts),
2804 PromotedInsts(PromotedInsts), TPT(TPT), LargeOffsetGEP(LargeOffsetGEP) {
2805 IgnoreProfitability = false;
2806 }
2807
2808public:
2809 /// Find the maximal addressing mode that a load/store of V can fold,
2810 /// give an access type of AccessTy. This returns a list of involved
2811 /// instructions in AddrModeInsts.
2812 /// \p InsertedInsts The instructions inserted by other CodeGenPrepare
2813 /// optimizations.
2814 /// \p PromotedInsts maps the instructions to their type before promotion.
2815 /// \p The ongoing transaction where every action should be registered.
2816 static ExtAddrMode
2817 Match(Value *V, Type *AccessTy, unsigned AS, Instruction *MemoryInst,
2818 SmallVectorImpl<Instruction *> &AddrModeInsts,
2819 const TargetLowering &TLI, const TargetRegisterInfo &TRI,
2820 const SetOfInstrs &InsertedInsts, InstrToOrigTy &PromotedInsts,
2821 TypePromotionTransaction &TPT,
2822 std::pair<AssertingVH<GetElementPtrInst>, int64_t> &LargeOffsetGEP) {
2823 ExtAddrMode Result;
2824
2825 bool Success = AddressingModeMatcher(AddrModeInsts, TLI, TRI, AccessTy, AS,
2826 MemoryInst, Result, InsertedInsts,
2827 PromotedInsts, TPT, LargeOffsetGEP)
2828 .matchAddr(V, 0);
2829 (void)Success; assert(Success && "Couldn't select *anything*?");
2830 return Result;
2831 }
2832
2833private:
2834 bool matchScaledValue(Value *ScaleReg, int64_t Scale, unsigned Depth);
2835 bool matchAddr(Value *Addr, unsigned Depth);
2836 bool matchOperationAddr(User *AddrInst, unsigned Opcode, unsigned Depth,
2837 bool *MovedAway = nullptr);
2838 bool isProfitableToFoldIntoAddressingMode(Instruction *I,
2839 ExtAddrMode &AMBefore,
2840 ExtAddrMode &AMAfter);
2841 bool valueAlreadyLiveAtInst(Value *Val, Value *KnownLive1, Value *KnownLive2);
2842 bool isPromotionProfitable(unsigned NewCost, unsigned OldCost,
2843 Value *PromotedOperand) const;
2844};

2846class PhiNodeSet;
2847
2848/// An iterator for PhiNodeSet.
2849class PhiNodeSetIterator {
2850 PhiNodeSet * const Set;
2851 size_t CurrentIndex = 0;
2852
2853public:
2854 /// The constructor. Start should point to either a valid element, or be equal
2855 /// to the size of the underlying SmallVector of the PhiNodeSet.
2856 PhiNodeSetIterator(PhiNodeSet * const Set, size_t Start);
2857 PHINode * operator*() const;
2858 PhiNodeSetIterator& operator++();
2859 bool operator==(const PhiNodeSetIterator &RHS) const;
2860 bool operator!=(const PhiNodeSetIterator &RHS) const;
2861};
2862
2863/// Keeps a set of PHINodes.
2864///
2865/// This is a minimal set implementation for a specific use case:
2866/// It is very fast when there are very few elements, but also provides good
2867/// performance when there are many. It is similar to SmallPtrSet, but also
2868/// provides iteration by insertion order, which is deterministic and stable
2869/// across runs. It is also similar to SmallSetVector, but provides removing
2870/// elements in O(1) time. This is achieved by not actually removing the element
2871/// from the underlying vector, so comes at the cost of using more memory, but
2872/// that is fine, since PhiNodeSets are used as short lived objects.
2873class PhiNodeSet {
2874 friend class PhiNodeSetIterator;
2875
2876 using MapType = SmallDenseMap<PHINode *, size_t, 32>;
2877 using iterator = PhiNodeSetIterator;
2878
2879 /// Keeps the elements in the order of their insertion in the underlying
2880 /// vector. To achieve constant time removal, it never deletes any element.
2881 SmallVector<PHINode *, 32> NodeList;
2882
2883 /// Keeps the elements in the underlying set implementation. This (and not the
2884 /// NodeList defined above) is the source of truth on whether an element
2885 /// is actually in the collection.
2886 MapType NodeMap;
2887
2888 /// Points to the first valid (not deleted) element when the set is not empty
2889 /// and the value is not zero. Equals to the size of the underlying vector
2890 /// when the set is empty. When the value is 0, as in the beginning, the
2891 /// first element may or may not be valid.
2892 size_t FirstValidElement = 0;
2893
2894public:
2895 /// Inserts a new element to the collection.
2896 /// \returns true if the element is actually added, i.e. was not in the
2897 /// collection before the operation.
2898 bool insert(PHINode *Ptr) {
2899 if (NodeMap.insert(std::make_pair(Ptr, NodeList.size())).second) {
2900 NodeList.push_back(Ptr);
2901 return true;
2902 }
2903 return false;
2904 }
2905
2906 /// Removes the element from the collection.
2907 /// \returns whether the element is actually removed, i.e. was in the
2908 /// collection before the operation.
2909 bool erase(PHINode *Ptr) {
2910 auto it = NodeMap.find(Ptr);
2911 if (it != NodeMap.end()) {
2912 NodeMap.erase(Ptr);
2913 SkipRemovedElements(FirstValidElement);
2914 return true;
2915 }
2916 return false;
2917 }
2918
2919 /// Removes all elements and clears the collection.
2920 void clear() {
2921 NodeMap.clear();
2922 NodeList.clear();
2923 FirstValidElement = 0;
2924 }
2925
2926 /// \returns an iterator that will iterate the elements in the order of
2927 /// insertion.
2928 iterator begin() {
2929 if (FirstValidElement == 0)
2930 SkipRemovedElements(FirstValidElement);
2931 return PhiNodeSetIterator(this, FirstValidElement);
2932 }
2933
2934 /// \returns an iterator that points to the end of the collection.
2935 iterator end() { return PhiNodeSetIterator(this, NodeList.size()); }
2936
2937 /// Returns the number of elements in the collection.
2938 size_t size() const {
2939 return NodeMap.size();
2940 }
2941
2942 /// \returns 1 if the given element is in the collection, and 0 if otherwise.
2943 size_t count(PHINode *Ptr) const {
2944 return NodeMap.count(Ptr);
2945 }
2946
2947private:
2948 /// Updates the CurrentIndex so that it will point to a valid element.
2949 ///
2950 /// If the element of NodeList at CurrentIndex is valid, it does not
2951 /// change it. If there are no more valid elements, it updates CurrentIndex
2952 /// to point to the end of the NodeList.
2953 void SkipRemovedElements(size_t &CurrentIndex) {
2954 while (CurrentIndex < NodeList.size()) {
2955 auto it = NodeMap.find(NodeList[CurrentIndex]);
2956 // If the element has been deleted and added again later, NodeMap will
2957 // point to a different index, so CurrentIndex will still be invalid.
2958 if (it != NodeMap.end() && it->second == CurrentIndex)
2959 break;
2960 ++CurrentIndex;
2961 }
2962 }
2963};
2964
2965PhiNodeSetIterator::PhiNodeSetIterator(PhiNodeSet *const Set, size_t Start)
2966 : Set(Set), CurrentIndex(Start) {}
2967
2968PHINode * PhiNodeSetIterator::operator*() const {
2969 assert(CurrentIndex < Set->NodeList.size() &&
2970 "PhiNodeSet access out of range");
2971 return Set->NodeList[CurrentIndex];
2972}
2973
2974PhiNodeSetIterator& PhiNodeSetIterator::operator++() {
2975 assert(CurrentIndex < Set->NodeList.size() &&
2976 "PhiNodeSet access out of range");
2977 ++CurrentIndex;
2978 Set->SkipRemovedElements(CurrentIndex);
2979 return *this;
2980}
2981
2982bool PhiNodeSetIterator::operator==(const PhiNodeSetIterator &RHS) const {
2983 return CurrentIndex == RHS.CurrentIndex;
2984}
2985
2986bool PhiNodeSetIterator::operator!=(const PhiNodeSetIterator &RHS) const {
2987 return !((*this) == RHS);
2988}
2989
2990/// Keep track of simplification of Phi nodes.
2991/// Accept the set of all phi nodes and erase phi node from this set
2992/// if it is simplified.
2993class SimplificationTracker {
2994 DenseMap<Value *, Value *> Storage;
2995 const SimplifyQuery &SQ;
2996 // Tracks newly created Phi nodes. The elements are iterated by insertion
2997 // order.
2998 PhiNodeSet AllPhiNodes;
2999 // Tracks newly created Select nodes.
3000 SmallPtrSet<SelectInst *, 32> AllSelectNodes;
3001
3002public:
3003 SimplificationTracker(const SimplifyQuery &sq)
3004 : SQ(sq) {}
3005
3006 Value *Get(Value *V) {
3007 do {
3008 auto SV = Storage.find(V);
3009 if (SV == Storage.end())
3010 return V;
3011 V = SV->second;
3012 } while (true);
3013 }
3014
3015 Value *Simplify(Value *Val) {
3016 SmallVector<Value *, 32> WorkList;
3017 SmallPtrSet<Value *, 32> Visited;
3018 WorkList.push_back(Val);
3019 while (!WorkList.empty()) {
3020 auto P = WorkList.pop_back_val();
3021 if (!Visited.insert(P).second)
3022 continue;
3023 if (auto *PI = dyn_cast<Instruction>(P))
3024 if (Value *V = SimplifyInstruction(cast<Instruction>(PI), SQ)) {
3025 for (auto *U : PI->users())
3026 WorkList.push_back(cast<Value>(U));
3027 Put(PI, V);
3028 PI->replaceAllUsesWith(V);
3029 if (auto *PHI = dyn_cast<PHINode>(PI))
3030 AllPhiNodes.erase(PHI);
3031 if (auto *Select = dyn_cast<SelectInst>(PI))
3032 AllSelectNodes.erase(Select);
3033 PI->eraseFromParent();
3034 }
3035 }
3036 return Get(Val);
3037 }
3038
3039 void Put(Value *From, Value *To) {
3040 Storage.insert({ From, To });
3041 }
3042
3043 void ReplacePhi(PHINode *From, PHINode *To) {
3044 Value* OldReplacement = Get(From);
3045 while (OldReplacement != From) {
3046 From = To;
3047 To = dyn_cast<PHINode>(OldReplacement);
3048 OldReplacement = Get(From);
3049 }
3050 assert(Get(To) == To && "Replacement PHI node is already replaced.");
3051 Put(From, To);
3052 From->replaceAllUsesWith(To);
3053 AllPhiNodes.erase(From);
3054 From->eraseFromParent();
3055 }
3056
3057 PhiNodeSet& newPhiNodes() { return AllPhiNodes; }
3058
3059 void insertNewPhi(PHINode *PN) { AllPhiNodes.insert(PN); }
3060
3061 void insertNewSelect(SelectInst *SI) { AllSelectNodes.insert(SI); }
3062
3063 unsigned countNewPhiNodes() const { return AllPhiNodes.size(); }
3064
3065 unsigned countNewSelectNodes() const { return AllSelectNodes.size(); }
3066
3067 void destroyNewNodes(Type *CommonType) {
3068 // For safe erasing, replace the uses with dummy value first.
3069 auto Dummy = UndefValue::get(CommonType);
3070 for (auto I : AllPhiNodes) {
3071 I->replaceAllUsesWith(Dummy);
3072 I->eraseFromParent();
3073 }
3074 AllPhiNodes.clear();
3075 for (auto I : AllSelectNodes) {
3076 I->replaceAllUsesWith(Dummy);
3077 I->eraseFromParent();
3078 }
3079 AllSelectNodes.clear();
3080 }
3081};
3082
3083/// A helper class for combining addressing modes.
3084class AddressingModeCombiner {
3085 typedef DenseMap<Value *, Value *> FoldAddrToValueMapping;
3086 typedef std::pair<PHINode *, PHINode *> PHIPair;
3087
3088private:
3089 /// The addressing modes we've collected.
3090 SmallVector<ExtAddrMode, 16> AddrModes;
3091
3092 /// The field in which the AddrModes differ, when we have more than one.
3093 ExtAddrMode::FieldName DifferentField = ExtAddrMode::NoField;
3094
3095 /// Are the AddrModes that we have all just equal to their original values?
3096 bool AllAddrModesTrivial = true;
3097
3098 /// Common Type for all different fields in addressing modes.
3099 Type *CommonType;
3100
3101 /// SimplifyQuery for simplifyInstruction utility.
3102 const SimplifyQuery &SQ;
3103
3104 /// Original Address.
3105 Value *Original;
3106
3107public:
3108 AddressingModeCombiner(const SimplifyQuery &_SQ, Value *OriginalValue)
3109 : CommonType(nullptr), SQ(_SQ), Original(OriginalValue) {}
3110
3111 /// Get the combined AddrMode
3112 const ExtAddrMode &getAddrMode() const {
3113 return AddrModes[0];
3114 }
3115
3116 /// Add a new AddrMode if it's compatible with the AddrModes we already
3117 /// have.
3118 /// \return True iff we succeeded in doing so.
3119 bool addNewAddrMode(ExtAddrMode &NewAddrMode) {
3120 // Take note of if we have any non-trivial AddrModes, as we need to detect
3121 // when all AddrModes are trivial as then we would introduce a phi or select
3122 // which just duplicates what's already there.
3123 AllAddrModesTrivial = AllAddrModesTrivial && NewAddrMode.isTrivial();
3124
3125 // If this is the first addrmode then everything is fine.
3126 if (AddrModes.empty()) {
3127 AddrModes.emplace_back(NewAddrMode);
3128 return true;
3129 }
3130
3131 // Figure out how different this is from the other address modes, which we
3132 // can do just by comparing against the first one given that we only care
3133 // about the cumulative difference.
3134 ExtAddrMode::FieldName ThisDifferentField =
3135 AddrModes[0].compare(NewAddrMode);
3136 if (DifferentField == ExtAddrMode::NoField)
3137 DifferentField = ThisDifferentField;
3138 else if (DifferentField != ThisDifferentField)
3139 DifferentField = ExtAddrMode::MultipleFields;
3140
3141 // If NewAddrMode differs in more than one dimension we cannot handle it.
3142 bool CanHandle = DifferentField != ExtAddrMode::MultipleFields;
3143
3144 // If Scale Field is different then we reject.
3145 CanHandle = CanHandle && DifferentField != ExtAddrMode::ScaleField;
3146
3147 // We also must reject the case when base offset is different and
3148 // scale reg is not null, we cannot handle this case due to merge of
3149 // different offsets will be used as ScaleReg.
3150 CanHandle = CanHandle && (DifferentField != ExtAddrMode::BaseOffsField ||
3151 !NewAddrMode.ScaledReg);
3152
3153 // We also must reject the case when GV is different and BaseReg installed
3154 // due to we want to use base reg as a merge of GV values.
3155 CanHandle = CanHandle && (DifferentField != ExtAddrMode::BaseGVField ||
3156 !NewAddrMode.HasBaseReg);
3157
3158 // Even if NewAddMode is the same we still need to collect it due to
3159 // original value is different. And later we will need all original values
3160 // as anchors during finding the common Phi node.
3161 if (CanHandle)
3162 AddrModes.emplace_back(NewAddrMode);
3163 else
3164 AddrModes.clear();
3165
3166 return CanHandle;
3167 }
3168
3169 /// Combine the addressing modes we've collected into a single
3170 /// addressing mode.
3171 /// \return True iff we successfully combined them or we only had one so
3172 /// didn't need to combine them anyway.
3173 bool combineAddrModes() {
3174 // If we have no AddrModes then they can't be combined.
3175 if (AddrModes.size() == 0)
3176 return false;
3177
3178 // A single AddrMode can trivially be combined.
3179 if (AddrModes.size() == 1 || DifferentField == ExtAddrMode::NoField)
3180 return true;
3181
3182 // If the AddrModes we collected are all just equal to the value they are
3183 // derived from then combining them wouldn't do anything useful.
3184 if (AllAddrModesTrivial)
3185 return false;
3186
3187 if (!addrModeCombiningAllowed())
3188 return false;
3189
3190 // Build a map between <original value, basic block where we saw it> to
3191 // value of base register.
3192 // Bail out if there is no common type.
3193 FoldAddrToValueMapping Map;
3194 if (!initializeMap(Map))
3195 return false;
3196
3197 Value *CommonValue = findCommon(Map);
3198 if (CommonValue)
3199 AddrModes[0].SetCombinedField(DifferentField, CommonValue, AddrModes);
3200 return CommonValue != nullptr;
3201 }
3202
3203private:
3204 /// Initialize Map with anchor values. For address seen
3205 /// we set the value of different field saw in this address.
3206 /// At the same time we find a common type for different field we will
3207 /// use to create new Phi/Select nodes. Keep it in CommonType field.
3208 /// Return false if there is no common type found.
3209 bool initializeMap(FoldAddrToValueMapping &Map) {
3210 // Keep track of keys where the value is null. We will need to replace it
3211 // with constant null when we know the common type.
3212 SmallVector<Value *, 2> NullValue;
3213 Type *IntPtrTy = SQ.DL.getIntPtrType(AddrModes[0].OriginalValue->getType());
3214 for (auto &AM : AddrModes) {
3215 Value *DV = AM.GetFieldAsValue(DifferentField, IntPtrTy);
3216 if (DV) {
3217 auto *Type = DV->getType();
3218 if (CommonType && CommonType != Type)
3219 return false;
3220 CommonType = Type;
3221 Map[AM.OriginalValue] = DV;
3222 } else {
3223 NullValue.push_back(AM.OriginalValue);
3224 }
3225 }
3226 assert(CommonType && "At least one non-null value must be!");
3227 for (auto *V : NullValue)
3228 Map[V] = Constant::getNullValue(CommonType);
3229 return true;
3230 }
3231
3232 /// We have mapping between value A and other value B where B was a field in
3233 /// addressing mode represented by A. Also we have an original value C
3234 /// representing an address we start with. Traversing from C through phi and
3235 /// selects we ended up with A's in a map. This utility function tries to find
3236 /// a value V which is a field in addressing mode C and traversing through phi
3237 /// nodes and selects we will end up in corresponded values B in a map.
3238 /// The utility will create a new Phi/Selects if needed.
3239 // The simple example looks as follows:
3240 // BB1:
3241 // p1 = b1 + 40
3242 // br cond BB2, BB3
3243 // BB2:
3244 // p2 = b2 + 40
3245 // br BB3
3246 // BB3:
3247 // p = phi [p1, BB1], [p2, BB2]
3248 // v = load p
3249 // Map is
3250 // p1 -> b1
3251 // p2 -> b2
3252 // Request is
3253 // p -> ?
3254 // The function tries to find or build phi [b1, BB1], [b2, BB2] in BB3.
3255 Value *findCommon(FoldAddrToValueMapping &Map) {
3256 // Tracks the simplification of newly created phi nodes. The reason we use
3257 // this mapping is because we will add new created Phi nodes in AddrToBase.
3258 // Simplification of Phi nodes is recursive, so some Phi node may
3259 // be simplified after we added it to AddrToBase. In reality this
3260 // simplification is possible only if original phi/selects were not
3261 // simplified yet.
3262 // Using this mapping we can find the current value in AddrToBase.
3263 SimplificationTracker ST(SQ);
3264
3265 // First step, DFS to create PHI nodes for all intermediate blocks.
3266 // Also fill traverse order for the second step.
3267 SmallVector<Value *, 32> TraverseOrder;
3268 InsertPlaceholders(Map, TraverseOrder, ST);
3269
3270 // Second Step, fill new nodes by merged values and simplify if possible.
3271 FillPlaceholders(Map, TraverseOrder, ST);
3272
3273 if (!AddrSinkNewSelects && ST.countNewSelectNodes() > 0) {
3274 ST.destroyNewNodes(CommonType);
3275 return nullptr;
3276 }
3277
3278 // Now we'd like to match New Phi nodes to existed ones.
3279 unsigned PhiNotMatchedCount = 0;
3280 if (!MatchPhiSet(ST, AddrSinkNewPhis, PhiNotMatchedCount)) {
3281 ST.destroyNewNodes(CommonType);
3282 return nullptr;
3283 }
3284
3285 auto *Result = ST.Get(Map.find(Original)->second);
3286 if (Result) {
3287 NumMemoryInstsPhiCreated += ST.countNewPhiNodes() + PhiNotMatchedCount;
3288 NumMemoryInstsSelectCreated += ST.countNewSelectNodes();
3289 }
3290 return Result;
3291 }
3292
3293 /// Try to match PHI node to Candidate.
3294 /// Matcher tracks the matched Phi nodes.
3295 bool MatchPhiNode(PHINode *PHI, PHINode *Candidate,
3296 SmallSetVector<PHIPair, 8> &Matcher,
3297 PhiNodeSet &PhiNodesToMatch) {
3298 SmallVector<PHIPair, 8> WorkList;
3299 Matcher.insert({ PHI, Candidate });
3300 SmallSet<PHINode *, 8> MatchedPHIs;
3301 MatchedPHIs.insert(PHI);
3302 WorkList.push_back({ PHI, Candidate });
3303 SmallSet<PHIPair, 8> Visited;
3304 while (!WorkList.empty()) {
3305 auto Item = WorkList.pop_back_val();
3306 if (!Visited.insert(Item).second)
3307 continue;
3308 // We iterate over all incoming values to Phi to compare them.
3309 // If values are different and both of them Phi and the first one is a
3310 // Phi we added (subject to match) and both of them is in the same basic
3311 // block then we can match our pair if values match. So we state that
3312 // these values match and add it to work list to verify that.
3313 for (auto B : Item.first->blocks()) {
3314 Value *FirstValue = Item.first->getIncomingValueForBlock(B);
3315 Value *SecondValue = Item.second->getIncomingValueForBlock(B);
3316 if (FirstValue == SecondValue)
3317 continue;
3318
3319 PHINode *FirstPhi = dyn_cast<PHINode>(FirstValue);
3320 PHINode *SecondPhi = dyn_cast<PHINode>(SecondValue);
3321
3322 // One of them is not Phi or
3323 // The first one is not Phi node from the set we'd like to match or
3324 // Phi nodes from different basic blocks then
3325 // we will not be able to match.
3326 if (!FirstPhi || !SecondPhi || !PhiNodesToMatch.count(FirstPhi) ||
3327 FirstPhi->getParent() != SecondPhi->getParent())
3328 return false;
3329
3330 // If we already matched them then continue.
3331 if (Matcher.count({ FirstPhi, SecondPhi }))
3332 continue;
3333 // So the values are different and does not match. So we need them to
3334 // match. (But we register no more than one match per PHI node, so that
3335 // we won't later try to replace them twice.)
3336 if (!MatchedPHIs.insert(FirstPhi).second)
3337 Matcher.insert({ FirstPhi, SecondPhi });
3338 // But me must check it.
3339 WorkList.push_back({ FirstPhi, SecondPhi });
3340 }
3341 }
3342 return true;
3343 }
3344
3345 /// For the given set of PHI nodes (in the SimplificationTracker) try
3346 /// to find their equivalents.
3347 /// Returns false if this matching fails and creation of new Phi is disabled.
3348 bool MatchPhiSet(SimplificationTracker &ST, bool AllowNewPhiNodes,
3349 unsigned &PhiNotMatchedCount) {
3350 // Matched and PhiNodesToMatch iterate their elements in a deterministic
3351 // order, so the replacements (ReplacePhi) are also done in a deterministic
3352 // order.
3353 SmallSetVector<PHIPair, 8> Matched;
3354 SmallPtrSet<PHINode *, 8> WillNotMatch;
3355 PhiNodeSet &PhiNodesToMatch = ST.newPhiNodes();
3356 while (PhiNodesToMatch.size()) {
3357 PHINode *PHI = *PhiNodesToMatch.begin();
3358
3359 // Add us, if no Phi nodes in the basic block we do not match.
3360 WillNotMatch.clear();
3361 WillNotMatch.insert(PHI);
3362
3363 // Traverse all Phis until we found equivalent or fail to do that.
3364 bool IsMatched = false;
3365 for (auto &P : PHI->getParent()->phis()) {
3366 if (&P == PHI)
3367 continue;
3368 if ((IsMatched = MatchPhiNode(PHI, &P, Matched, PhiNodesToMatch)))
3369 break;
3370 // If it does not match, collect all Phi nodes from matcher.
3371 // if we end up with no match, them all these Phi nodes will not match
3372 // later.
3373 for (auto M : Matched)
3374 WillNotMatch.insert(M.first);
3375 Matched.clear();
3376 }
3377 if (IsMatched) {
3378 // Replace all matched values and erase them.
3379 for (auto MV : Matched)
3380 ST.ReplacePhi(MV.first, MV.second);
3381 Matched.clear();
3382 continue;
3383 }
3384 // If we are not allowed to create new nodes then bail out.
3385 if (!AllowNewPhiNodes)
3386 return false;
3387 // Just remove all seen values in matcher. They will not match anything.
3388 PhiNotMatchedCount += WillNotMatch.size();
3389 for (auto *P : WillNotMatch)
3390 PhiNodesToMatch.erase(P);
3391 }
3392 return true;
3393 }
3394 /// Fill the placeholders with values from predecessors and simplify them.
3395 void FillPlaceholders(FoldAddrToValueMapping &Map,
3396 SmallVectorImpl<Value *> &TraverseOrder,
3397 SimplificationTracker &ST) {
3398 while (!TraverseOrder.empty()) {
3399 Value *Current = TraverseOrder.pop_back_val();
3400 assert(Map.find(Current) != Map.end() && "No node to fill!!!");
3401 Value *V = Map[Current];
3402
3403 if (SelectInst *Select = dyn_cast<SelectInst>(V)) {
3404 // CurrentValue also must be Select.
3405 auto *CurrentSelect = cast<SelectInst>(Current);
3406 auto *TrueValue = CurrentSelect->getTrueValue();
3407 assert(Map.find(TrueValue) != Map.end() && "No True Value!");
3408 Select->setTrueValue(ST.Get(Map[TrueValue]));
3409 auto *FalseValue = CurrentSelect->getFalseValue();
3410 assert(Map.find(FalseValue) != Map.end() && "No False Value!");
3411 Select->setFalseValue(ST.Get(Map[FalseValue]));
3412 } else {
3413 // Must be a Phi node then.
3414 PHINode *PHI = cast<PHINode>(V);
3415 auto *CurrentPhi = dyn_cast<PHINode>(Current);
3416 // Fill the Phi node with values from predecessors.
3417 for (auto B : predecessors(PHI->getParent())) {
3418 Value *PV = CurrentPhi->getIncomingValueForBlock(B);
3419 assert(Map.find(PV) != Map.end() && "No predecessor Value!");
3420 PHI->addIncoming(ST.Get(Map[PV]), B);
3421 }
3422 }
3423 Map[Current] = ST.Simplify(V);
3424 }
3425 }
3426
3427 /// Starting from original value recursively iterates over def-use chain up to
3428 /// known ending values represented in a map. For each traversed phi/select
3429 /// inserts a placeholder Phi or Select.
3430 /// Reports all new created Phi/Select nodes by adding them to set.
3431 /// Also reports and order in what values have been traversed.
3432 void InsertPlaceholders(FoldAddrToValueMapping &Map,
3433 SmallVectorImpl<Value *> &TraverseOrder,
3434 SimplificationTracker &ST) {
3435 SmallVector<Value *, 32> Worklist;
3436 assert((isa<PHINode>(Original) || isa<SelectInst>(Original)) &&
3437 "Address must be a Phi or Select node");
3438 auto *Dummy = UndefValue::get(CommonType);
3439 Worklist.push_back(Original);
3440 while (!Worklist.empty()) {
3441 Value *Current = Worklist.pop_back_val();
3442 // if it is already visited or it is an ending value then skip it.
3443 if (Map.find(Current) != Map.end())
3444 continue;
3445 TraverseOrder.push_back(Current);
3446
3447 // CurrentValue must be a Phi node or select. All others must be covered
3448 // by anchors.
3449 if (SelectInst *CurrentSelect = dyn_cast<SelectInst>(Current)) {
3450 // Is it OK to get metadata from OrigSelect?!
3451 // Create a Select placeholder with dummy value.
3452 SelectInst *Select = SelectInst::Create(
3453 CurrentSelect->getCondition(), Dummy, Dummy,
3454 CurrentSelect->getName(), CurrentSelect, CurrentSelect);
3455 Map[Current] = Select;
3456 ST.insertNewSelect(Select);
3457 // We are interested in True and False values.
3458 Worklist.push_back(CurrentSelect->getTrueValue());
3459 Worklist.push_back(CurrentSelect->getFalseValue());
3460 } else {
3461 // It must be a Phi node then.
3462 PHINode *CurrentPhi = cast<PHINode>(Current);
3463 unsigned PredCount = CurrentPhi->getNumIncomingValues();
3464 PHINode *PHI =
3465 PHINode::Create(CommonType, PredCount, "sunk_phi", CurrentPhi);
3466 Map[Current] = PHI;
3467 ST.insertNewPhi(PHI);
3468 for (Value *P : CurrentPhi->incoming_values())
3469 Worklist.push_back(P);
3470 }
3471 }
3472 }
3473
3474 bool addrModeCombiningAllowed() {
3475 if (DisableComplexAddrModes)
3476 return false;
3477 switch (DifferentField) {
3478 default:
3479 return false;
3480 case ExtAddrMode::BaseRegField:
3481 return AddrSinkCombineBaseReg;
3482 case ExtAddrMode::BaseGVField:
3483 return AddrSinkCombineBaseGV;
3484 case ExtAddrMode::BaseOffsField:
3485 return AddrSinkCombineBaseOffs;
3486 case ExtAddrMode::ScaledRegField:
3487 return AddrSinkCombineScaledReg;
3488 }
3489 }
3490};
3491} // end anonymous namespace
3492
3493/// Try adding ScaleReg*Scale to the current addressing mode.
3494/// Return true and update AddrMode if this addr mode is legal for the target,
3495/// false if not.
3496bool AddressingModeMatcher::matchScaledValue(Value *ScaleReg, int64_t Scale,
3497 unsigned Depth) {
3498 // If Scale is 1, then this is the same as adding ScaleReg to the addressing
3499 // mode. Just process that directly.
3500 if (Scale == 1)
3501 return matchAddr(ScaleReg, Depth);
3502
3503 // If the scale is 0, it takes nothing to add this.
3504 if (Scale == 0)
3505 return true;
3506
3507 // If we already have a scale of this value, we can add to it, otherwise, we
3508 // need an available scale field.
3509 if (AddrMode.Scale != 0 && AddrMode.ScaledReg != ScaleReg)
3510 return false;
3511
3512 ExtAddrMode TestAddrMode = AddrMode;
3513
3514 // Add scale to turn X*4+X*3 -> X*7. This could also do things like
3515 // [A+B + A*7] -> [B+A*8].
3516 TestAddrMode.Scale += Scale;
3517 TestAddrMode.ScaledReg = ScaleReg;
3518
3519 // If the new address isn't legal, bail out.
3520 if (!TLI.isLegalAddressingMode(DL, TestAddrMode, AccessTy, AddrSpace))
3521 return false;
3522
3523 // It was legal, so commit it.
3524 AddrMode = TestAddrMode;
3525
3526 // Okay, we decided that we can add ScaleReg+Scale to AddrMode. Check now
3527 // to see if ScaleReg is actually X+C. If so, we can turn this into adding
3528 // X*Scale + C*Scale to addr mode.
3529 ConstantInt *CI = nullptr; Value *AddLHS = nullptr;
3530 if (isa<Instruction>(ScaleReg) && // not a constant expr.
3531 match(ScaleReg, m_Add(m_Value(AddLHS), m_ConstantInt(CI)))) {
3532 TestAddrMode.InBounds = false;
3533 TestAddrMode.ScaledReg = AddLHS;
3534 TestAddrMode.BaseOffs += CI->getSExtValue()*TestAddrMode.Scale;
3535
3536 // If this addressing mode is legal, commit it and remember that we folded
3537 // this instruction.
3538 if (TLI.isLegalAddressingMode(DL, TestAddrMode, AccessTy, AddrSpace)) {
3539 AddrModeInsts.push_back(cast<Instruction>(ScaleReg));
3540 AddrMode = TestAddrMode;
3541 return true;
3542 }
3543 }
3544
3545 // Otherwise, not (x+c)*scale, just return what we have.
3546 return true;
3547}
3548
3549/// This is a little filter, which returns true if an addressing computation
3550/// involving I might be folded into a load/store accessing it.
3551/// This doesn't need to be perfect, but needs to accept at least
3552/// the set of instructions that MatchOperationAddr can.
3553static bool MightBeFoldableInst(Instruction *I) {
3554 switch (I->getOpcode()) {
3555 case Instruction::BitCast:
3556 case Instruction::AddrSpaceCast:
3557 // Don't touch identity bitcasts.
3558 if (I->getType() == I->getOperand(0)->getType())
3559 return false;
3560 return I->getType()->isIntOrPtrTy();
3561 case Instruction::PtrToInt:
3562 // PtrToInt is always a noop, as we know that the int type is pointer sized.
3563 return true;
3564 case Instruction::IntToPtr:
3565 // We know the input is intptr_t, so this is foldable.
3566 return true;
3567 case Instruction::Add:
3568 return true;
3569 case Instruction::Mul:
3570 case Instruction::Shl:
3571 // Can only handle X*C and X << C.
3572 return isa<ConstantInt>(I->getOperand(1));
3573 case Instruction::GetElementPtr:
3574 return true;
3575 default:
3576 return false;
3577 }
3578}
3579
3580/// Check whether or not \p Val is a legal instruction for \p TLI.
3581/// \note \p Val is assumed to be the product of some type promotion.
3582/// Therefore if \p Val has an undefined state in \p TLI, this is assumed
3583/// to be legal, as the non-promoted value would have had the same state.
3584static bool isPromotedInstructionLegal(const TargetLowering &TLI,
3585 const DataLayout &DL, Value *Val) {
3586 Instruction *PromotedInst = dyn_cast<Instruction>(Val);
3587 if (!PromotedInst)
3588 return false;
3589 int ISDOpcode = TLI.InstructionOpcodeToISD(PromotedInst->getOpcode());
3590 // If the ISDOpcode is undefined, it was undefined before the promotion.
3591 if (!ISDOpcode)
3592 return true;
3593 // Otherwise, check if the promoted instruction is legal or not.
3594 return TLI.isOperationLegalOrCustom(
3595 ISDOpcode, TLI.getValueType(DL, PromotedInst->getType()));
3596}
3597
3598namespace {
3599
3600/// Hepler class to perform type promotion.
3601class TypePromotionHelper {
3602 /// Utility function to add a promoted instruction \p ExtOpnd to
3603 /// \p PromotedInsts and record the type of extension we have seen.
3604 static void addPromotedInst(InstrToOrigTy &PromotedInsts,
3605 Instruction *ExtOpnd,
3606 bool IsSExt) {
3607 ExtType ExtTy = IsSExt ? SignExtension : ZeroExtension;
3608 InstrToOrigTy::iterator It = PromotedInsts.find(ExtOpnd);
3609 if (It != PromotedInsts.end()) {
3610 // If the new extension is same as original, the information in
3611 // PromotedInsts[ExtOpnd] is still correct.
3612 if (It->second.getInt() == ExtTy)
3613 return;
3614
3615 // Now the new extension is different from old extension, we make
3616 // the type information invalid by setting extension type to
3617 // BothExtension.
3618 ExtTy = BothExtension;
3619 }
3620 PromotedInsts[ExtOpnd] = TypeIsSExt(ExtOpnd->getType(), ExtTy);
3621 }
3622
3623 /// Utility function to query the original type of instruction \p Opnd
3624 /// with a matched extension type. If the extension doesn't match, we
3625 /// cannot use the information we had on the original type.
3626 /// BothExtension doesn't match any extension type.
3627 static const Type *getOrigType(const InstrToOrigTy &PromotedInsts,
3628 Instruction *Opnd,
3629 bool IsSExt) {
3630 ExtType ExtTy = IsSExt ? SignExtension : ZeroExtension;
3631 InstrToOrigTy::const_iterator It = PromotedInsts.find(Opnd);
3632 if (It != PromotedInsts.end() && It->second.getInt() == ExtTy)
3633 return It->second.getPointer();
3634 return nullptr;
3635 }
3636
3637 /// Utility function to check whether or not a sign or zero extension
3638 /// of \p Inst with \p ConsideredExtType can be moved through \p Inst by
3639 /// either using the operands of \p Inst or promoting \p Inst.
3640 /// The type of the extension is defined by \p IsSExt.
3641 /// In other words, check if:
3642 /// ext (Ty Inst opnd1 opnd2 ... opndN) to ConsideredExtType.
3643 /// #1 Promotion applies:
3644 /// ConsideredExtType Inst (ext opnd1 to ConsideredExtType, ...).
3645 /// #2 Operand reuses:
3646 /// ext opnd1 to ConsideredExtType.
3647 /// \p PromotedInsts maps the instructions to their type before promotion.
3648 static bool canGetThrough(const Instruction *Inst, Type *ConsideredExtType,
3649 const InstrToOrigTy &PromotedInsts, bool IsSExt);
3650
3651 /// Utility function to determine if \p OpIdx should be promoted when
3652 /// promoting \p Inst.
3653 static bool shouldExtOperand(const Instruction *Inst, int OpIdx) {
3654 return !(isa<SelectInst>(Inst) && OpIdx == 0);
3655 }
3656
3657 /// Utility function to promote the operand of \p Ext when this
3658 /// operand is a promotable trunc or sext or zext.
3659 /// \p PromotedInsts maps the instructions to their type before promotion.
3660 /// \p CreatedInstsCost[out] contains the cost of all instructions
3661 /// created to promote the operand of Ext.
3662 /// Newly added extensions are inserted in \p Exts.
3663 /// Newly added truncates are inserted in \p Truncs.
3664 /// Should never be called directly.
3665 /// \return The promoted value which is used instead of Ext.
3666 static Value *promoteOperandForTruncAndAnyExt(
3667 Instruction *Ext, TypePromotionTransaction &TPT,
3668 InstrToOrigTy &PromotedInsts, unsigned &CreatedInstsCost,
3669 SmallVectorImpl<Instruction *> *Exts,
3670 SmallVectorImpl<Instruction *> *Truncs, const TargetLowering &TLI);
3671
3672 /// Utility function to promote the operand of \p Ext when this
3673 /// operand is promotable and is not a supported trunc or sext.
3674 /// \p PromotedInsts maps the instructions to their type before promotion.
3675 /// \p CreatedInstsCost[out] contains the cost of all the instructions
3676 /// created to promote the operand of Ext.
3677 /// Newly added extensions are inserted in \p Exts.
3678 /// Newly added truncates are inserted in \p Truncs.
3679 /// Should never be called directly.
3680 /// \return The promoted value which is used instead of Ext.
3681 static Value *promoteOperandForOther(Instruction *Ext,
3682 TypePromotionTransaction &TPT,
3683 InstrToOrigTy &PromotedInsts,
3684 unsigned &CreatedInstsCost,
3685 SmallVectorImpl<Instruction *> *Exts,
3686 SmallVectorImpl<Instruction *> *Truncs,
3687 const TargetLowering &TLI, bool IsSExt);
3688
3689 /// \see promoteOperandForOther.
3690 static Value *signExtendOperandForOther(
3691 Instruction *Ext, TypePromotionTransaction &TPT,
3692 InstrToOrigTy &PromotedInsts, unsigned &CreatedInstsCost,
3693 SmallVectorImpl<Instruction *> *Exts,
3694 SmallVectorImpl<Instruction *> *Truncs, const TargetLowering &TLI) {
3695 return promoteOperandForOther(Ext, TPT, PromotedInsts, CreatedInstsCost,
3696 Exts, Truncs, TLI, true);
3697 }
3698
3699 /// \see promoteOperandForOther.
3700 static Value *zeroExtendOperandForOther(
3701 Instruction *Ext, TypePromotionTransaction &TPT,
3702 InstrToOrigTy &PromotedInsts, unsigned &CreatedInstsCost,
3703 SmallVectorImpl<Instruction *> *Exts,
3704 SmallVectorImpl<Instruction *> *Truncs, const TargetLowering &TLI) {
3705 return promoteOperandForOther(Ext, TPT, PromotedInsts, CreatedInstsCost,
3706 Exts, Truncs, TLI, false);
3707 }
3708
3709public:
3710 /// Type for the utility function that promotes the operand of Ext.
3711 using Action = Value *(*)(Instruction *Ext, TypePromotionTransaction &TPT,
3712 InstrToOrigTy &PromotedInsts,
3713 unsigned &CreatedInstsCost,
3714 SmallVectorImpl<Instruction *> *Exts,
3715 SmallVectorImpl<Instruction *> *Truncs,
3716 const TargetLowering &TLI);
3717
3718 /// Given a sign/zero extend instruction \p Ext, return the appropriate
3719 /// action to promote the operand of \p Ext instead of using Ext.
3720 /// \return NULL if no promotable action is possible with the current
3721 /// sign extension.
3722 /// \p InsertedInsts keeps track of all the instructions inserted by the
3723 /// other CodeGenPrepare optimizations. This information is important
3724 /// because we do not want to promote these instructions as CodeGenPrepare
3725 /// will reinsert them later. Thus creating an infinite loop: create/remove.
3726 /// \p PromotedInsts maps the instructions to their type before promotion.
3727 static Action getAction(Instruction *Ext, const SetOfInstrs &InsertedInsts,
3728 const TargetLowering &TLI,
3729 const InstrToOrigTy &PromotedInsts);
3730};
3731
3732} // end anonymous namespace
3733
3734bool TypePromotionHelper::canGetThrough(const Instruction *Inst,
3735 Type *ConsideredExtType,
3736 const InstrToOrigTy &PromotedInsts,
3737 bool IsSExt) {
3738 // The promotion helper does not know how to deal with vector types yet.
3739 // To be able to fix that, we would need to fix the places where we
3740 // statically extend, e.g., constants and such.
3741 if (Inst->getType()->isVectorTy())
3742 return false;
3743
3744 // We can always get through zext.
3745 if (isa<ZExtInst>(Inst))
3746 return true;
3747
3748 // sext(sext) is ok too.
3749 if (IsSExt && isa<SExtInst>(Inst))
3750 return true;
3751
3752 // We can get through binary operator, if it is legal. In other words, the
3753 // binary operator must have a nuw or nsw flag.
3754 const BinaryOperator *BinOp = dyn_cast<BinaryOperator>(Inst);
3755 if (BinOp && isa<OverflowingBinaryOperator>(BinOp) &&
3756 ((!IsSExt && BinOp->hasNoUnsignedWrap()) ||
3757 (IsSExt && BinOp->hasNoSignedWrap())))
3758 return true;
3759
3760 // ext(and(opnd, cst)) --> and(ext(opnd), ext(cst))
3761 if ((Inst->getOpcode() == Instruction::And ||
3762 Inst->getOpcode() == Instruction::Or))
3763 return true;
3764
3765 // ext(xor(opnd, cst)) --> xor(ext(opnd), ext(cst))
3766 if (Inst->getOpcode() == Instruction::Xor) {
3767 const ConstantInt *Cst = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(Inst->getOperand(1));
3768 // Make sure it is not a NOT.
3769 if (Cst && !Cst->getValue().isAllOnesValue())
3770 return true;
3771 }
3772
3773 // zext(shrl(opnd, cst)) --> shrl(zext(opnd), zext(cst))
3774 // It may change a poisoned value into a regular value, like
3775 // zext i32 (shrl i8 %val, 12) --> shrl i32 (zext i8 %val), 12
3776 // poisoned value regular value
3777 // It should be OK since undef covers valid value.
3778 if (Inst->getOpcode() == Instruction::LShr && !IsSExt)
3779 return true;
3780
3781 // and(ext(shl(opnd, cst)), cst) --> and(shl(ext(opnd), ext(cst)), cst)
3782 // It may change a poisoned value into a regular value, like
3783 // zext i32 (shl i8 %val, 12) --> shl i32 (zext i8 %val), 12
3784 // poisoned value regular value
3785 // It should be OK since undef covers valid value.
3786 if (Inst->getOpcode() == Instruction::Shl && Inst->hasOneUse()) {
3787 const Instruction *ExtInst =
3788 dyn_cast<const Instruction>(*Inst->user_begin());
3789 if (ExtInst->hasOneUse()) {
3790 const Instruction *AndInst =
3791 dyn_cast<const Instruction>(*ExtInst->user_begin());
3792 if (AndInst && AndInst->getOpcode() == Instruction::And) {
3793 const ConstantInt *Cst = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(AndInst->getOperand(1));
3794 if (Cst &&
3795 Cst->getValue().isIntN(Inst->getType()->getIntegerBitWidth()))
3796 return true;
3797 }
3798 }
3799 }
3800
3801 // Check if we can do the following simplification.
3802 // ext(trunc(opnd)) --> ext(opnd)
3803 if (!isa<TruncInst>(Inst))
3804 return false;
3805
3806 Value *OpndVal = Inst->getOperand(0);
3807 // Check if we can use this operand in the extension.
3808 // If the type is larger than the result type of the extension, we cannot.
3809 if (!OpndVal->getType()->isIntegerTy() ||
3810 OpndVal->getType()->getIntegerBitWidth() >
3811 ConsideredExtType->getIntegerBitWidth())
3812 return false;
3813
3814 // If the operand of the truncate is not an instruction, we will not have
3815 // any information on the dropped bits.
3816 // (Actually we could for constant but it is not worth the extra logic).
3817 Instruction *Opnd = dyn_cast<Instruction>(OpndVal);
3818 if (!Opnd)
3819 return false;
3820
3821 // Check if the source of the type is narrow enough.
3822 // I.e., check that trunc just drops extended bits of the same kind of
3823 // the extension.
3824 // #1 get the type of the operand and check the kind of the extended bits.
3825 const Type *OpndType = getOrigType(PromotedInsts, Opnd, IsSExt);
3826 if (OpndType)
3827 ;
3828 else if ((IsSExt && isa<SExtInst>(Opnd)) || (!IsSExt && isa<ZExtInst>(Opnd)))
3829 OpndType = Opnd->getOperand(0)->getType();
3830 else
3831 return false;
3832
3833 // #2 check that the truncate just drops extended bits.
3834 return Inst->getType()->getIntegerBitWidth() >=
3835 OpndType->getIntegerBitWidth();
3836}
3837
3838TypePromotionHelper::Action TypePromotionHelper::getAction(
3839 Instruction *Ext, const SetOfInstrs &InsertedInsts,
3840 const TargetLowering &TLI, const InstrToOrigTy &PromotedInsts) {
3841 assert((isa<SExtInst>(Ext) || isa<ZExtInst>(Ext)) &&
3842 "Unexpected instruction type");
3843 Instruction *ExtOpnd = dyn_cast<Instruction>(Ext->getOperand(0));
3844 Type *ExtTy = Ext->getType();
3845 bool IsSExt = isa<SExtInst>(Ext);
3846 // If the operand of the extension is not an instruction, we cannot
3847 // get through.
3848 // If it, check we can get through.
3849 if (!ExtOpnd || !canGetThrough(ExtOpnd, ExtTy, PromotedInsts, IsSExt))
3850 return nullptr;
3851
3852 // Do not promote if the operand has been added by codegenprepare.
3853 // Otherwise, it means we are undoing an optimization that is likely to be
3854 // redone, thus causing potential infinite loop.
3855 if (isa<TruncInst>(ExtOpnd) && InsertedInsts.count(ExtOpnd))
3856 return nullptr;
3857
3858 // SExt or Trunc instructions.
3859 // Return the related handler.
3860 if (isa<SExtInst>(ExtOpnd) || isa<TruncInst>(ExtOpnd) ||
3861 isa<ZExtInst>(ExtOpnd))
3862 return promoteOperandForTruncAndAnyExt;
3863
3864 // Regular instruction.
3865 // Abort early if we will have to insert non-free instructions.
3866 if (!ExtOpnd->hasOneUse() && !TLI.isTruncateFree(ExtTy, ExtOpnd->getType()))
3867 return nullptr;
3868 return IsSExt ? signExtendOperandForOther : zeroExtendOperandForOther;
3869}
3870
3871Value *TypePromotionHelper::promoteOperandForTruncAndAnyExt(
3872 Instruction *SExt, TypePromotionTransaction &TPT,
3873 InstrToOrigTy &PromotedInsts, unsigned &CreatedInstsCost,
3874 SmallVectorImpl<Instruction *> *Exts,
3875 SmallVectorImpl<Instruction *> *Truncs, const TargetLowering &TLI) {
3876 // By construction, the operand of SExt is an instruction. Otherwise we cannot
3877 // get through it and this method should not be called.
3878 Instruction *SExtOpnd = cast<Instruction>(SExt->getOperand(0));
3879 Value *ExtVal = SExt;
3880 bool HasMergedNonFreeExt = false;
3881 if (isa<ZExtInst>(SExtOpnd)) {
3882 // Replace s|zext(zext(opnd))
3883 // => zext(opnd).
3884 HasMergedNonFreeExt = !TLI.isExtFree(SExtOpnd);
3885 Value *ZExt =
3886 TPT.createZExt(SExt, SExtOpnd->getOperand(0), SExt->getType());
3887 TPT.replaceAllUsesWith(SExt, ZExt);
3888 TPT.eraseInstruction(SExt);
3889 ExtVal = ZExt;
3890 } else {
3891 // Replace z|sext(trunc(opnd)) or sext(sext(opnd))
3892 // => z|sext(opnd).
3893 TPT.setOperand(SExt, 0, SExtOpnd->getOperand(0));
3894 }
3895 CreatedInstsCost = 0;
3896
3897 // Remove dead code.
3898 if (SExtOpnd->use_empty())
3899 TPT.eraseInstruction(SExtOpnd);
3900
3901 // Check if the extension is still needed.
3902 Instruction *ExtInst = dyn_cast<Instruction>(ExtVal);
3903 if (!ExtInst || ExtInst->getType() != ExtInst->getOperand(0)->getType()) {
3904 if (ExtInst) {
3905 if (Exts)
3906 Exts->push_back(ExtInst);
3907 CreatedInstsCost = !TLI.isExtFree(ExtInst) && !HasMergedNonFreeExt;
3908 }
3909 return ExtVal;
3910 }
3911
3912 // At this point we have: ext ty opnd to ty.
3913 // Reassign the uses of ExtInst to the opnd and remove ExtInst.
3914 Value *NextVal = ExtInst->getOperand(0);
3915 TPT.eraseInstruction(ExtInst, NextVal);
3916 return NextVal;
3917}
3918
3919Value *TypePromotionHelper::promoteOperandForOther(
3920 Instruction *Ext, TypePromotionTransaction &TPT,
3921 InstrToOrigTy &PromotedInsts, unsigned &CreatedInstsCost,
3922 SmallVectorImpl<Instruction *> *Exts,
3923 SmallVectorImpl<Instruction *> *Truncs, const TargetLowering &TLI,
3924 bool IsSExt) {
3925 // By construction, the operand of Ext is an instruction. Otherwise we cannot
3926 // get through it and this method should not be called.
3927 Instruction *ExtOpnd = cast<Instruction>(Ext->getOperand(0));
3928 CreatedInstsCost = 0;
3929 if (!ExtOpnd->hasOneUse()) {
3930 // ExtOpnd will be promoted.
3931 // All its uses, but Ext, will need to use a truncated value of the
3932 // promoted version.
3933 // Create the truncate now.
3934 Value *Trunc = TPT.createTrunc(Ext, ExtOpnd->getType());
3935 if (Instruction *ITrunc = dyn_cast<Instruction>(Trunc)) {
3936 // Insert it just after the definition.
3937 ITrunc->moveAfter(ExtOpnd);
3938 if (Truncs)
3939 Truncs->push_back(ITrunc);
3940 }
3941
3942 TPT.replaceAllUsesWith(ExtOpnd, Trunc);
3943 // Restore the operand of Ext (which has been replaced by the previous call
3944 // to replaceAllUsesWith) to avoid creating a cycle trunc <-> sext.
3945 TPT.setOperand(Ext, 0, ExtOpnd);
3946 }
3947
3948 // Get through the Instruction:
3949 // 1. Update its type.
3950 // 2. Replace the uses of Ext by Inst.
3951 // 3. Extend each operand that needs to be extended.
3952
3953 // Remember the original type of the instruction before promotion.
3954 // This is useful to know that the high bits are sign extended bits.
3955 addPromotedInst(PromotedInsts, ExtOpnd, IsSExt);
3956 // Step #1.
3957 TPT.mutateType(ExtOpnd, Ext->getType());
3958 // Step #2.
3959 TPT.replaceAllUsesWith(Ext, ExtOpnd);
3960 // Step #3.
3961 Instruction *ExtForOpnd = Ext;
3962
3963 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Propagate Ext to operands\n");
3964 for (int OpIdx = 0, EndOpIdx = ExtOpnd->getNumOperands(); OpIdx != EndOpIdx;
3965 ++OpIdx) {
3966 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Operand:\n" << *(ExtOpnd->getOperand(OpIdx)) << '\n');
3967 if (ExtOpnd->getOperand(OpIdx)->getType() == Ext->getType() ||
3968 !shouldExtOperand(ExtOpnd, OpIdx)) {
3969 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "No need to propagate\n");
3970 continue;
3971 }
3972 // Check if we can statically extend the operand.
3973 Value *Opnd = ExtOpnd->getOperand(OpIdx);
3974 if (const ConstantInt *Cst = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(Opnd)) {
3975 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Statically extend\n");
3976 unsigned BitWidth = Ext->getType()->getIntegerBitWidth();
3977 APInt CstVal = IsSExt ? Cst->getValue().sext(BitWidth)
3978 : Cst->getValue().zext(BitWidth);
3979 TPT.setOperand(ExtOpnd, OpIdx, ConstantInt::get(Ext->getType(), CstVal));
3980 continue;
3981 }
3982 // UndefValue are typed, so we have to statically sign extend them.
3983 if (isa<UndefValue>(Opnd)) {
3984 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Statically extend\n");
3985 TPT.setOperand(ExtOpnd, OpIdx, UndefValue::get(Ext->getType()));
3986 continue;
3987 }
3988
3989 // Otherwise we have to explicitly sign extend the operand.
3990 // Check if Ext was reused to extend an operand.
3991 if (!ExtForOpnd) {
3992 // If yes, create a new one.
3993 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "More operands to ext\n");
3994 Value *ValForExtOpnd = IsSExt ? TPT.createSExt(Ext, Opnd, Ext->getType())
3995 : TPT.createZExt(Ext, Opnd, Ext->getType());
3996 if (!isa<Instruction>(ValForExtOpnd)) {
3997 TPT.setOperand(ExtOpnd, OpIdx, ValForExtOpnd);
3998 continue;
3999 }
4000 ExtForOpnd = cast<Instruction>(ValForExtOpnd);
4001 }
4002 if (Exts)
4003 Exts->push_back(ExtForOpnd);
4004 TPT.setOperand(ExtForOpnd, 0, Opnd);
4005
4006 // Move the sign extension before the insertion point.
4007 TPT.moveBefore(ExtForOpnd, ExtOpnd);
4008 TPT.setOperand(ExtOpnd, OpIdx, ExtForOpnd);
4009 CreatedInstsCost += !TLI.isExtFree(ExtForOpnd);
4010 // If more sext are required, new instructions will have to be created.
4011 ExtForOpnd = nullptr;
4012 }
4013 if (ExtForOpnd == Ext) {
4014 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Extension is useless now\n");
4015 TPT.eraseInstruction(Ext);
4016 }
4017 return ExtOpnd;
4018}
4019
4020/// Check whether or not promoting an instruction to a wider type is profitable.
4021/// \p NewCost gives the cost of extension instructions created by the
4022/// promotion.
4023/// \p OldCost gives the cost of extension instructions before the promotion
4024/// plus the number of instructions that have been
4025/// matched in the addressing mode the promotion.
4026/// \p PromotedOperand is the value that has been promoted.
4027/// \return True if the promotion is profitable, false otherwise.
4028bool AddressingModeMatcher::isPromotionProfitable(
4029 unsigned NewCost, unsigned OldCost, Value *PromotedOperand) const {
4030 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "OldCost: " << OldCost << "\tNewCost: " << NewCost
4031 << '\n');
4032 // The cost of the new extensions is greater than the cost of the
4033 // old extension plus what we folded.
4034 // This is not profitable.
4035 if (NewCost > OldCost)
4036 return false;
4037 if (NewCost < OldCost)
4038 return true;
4039 // The promotion is neutral but it may help folding the sign extension in
4040 // loads for instance.
4041 // Check that we did not create an illegal instruction.
4042 return isPromotedInstructionLegal(TLI, DL, PromotedOperand);
4043}
4044
4045/// Given an instruction or constant expr, see if we can fold the operation
4046/// into the addressing mode. If so, update the addressing mode and return
4047/// true, otherwise return false without modifying AddrMode.
4048/// If \p MovedAway is not NULL, it contains the information of whether or
4049/// not AddrInst has to be folded into the addressing mode on success.
4050/// If \p MovedAway == true, \p AddrInst will not be part of the addressing
4051/// because it has been moved away.
4052/// Thus AddrInst must not be added in the matched instructions.
4053/// This state can happen when AddrInst is a sext, since it may be moved away.
4054/// Therefore, AddrInst may not be valid when MovedAway is true and it must
4055/// not be referenced anymore.
4056bool AddressingModeMatcher::matchOperationAddr(User *AddrInst, unsigned Opcode,
4057 unsigned Depth,
4058 bool *MovedAway) {
4059 // Avoid exponential behavior on extremely deep expression trees.
4060 if (Depth >= 5) return false;
4061
4062 // By default, all matched instructions stay in place.
4063 if (MovedAway)
4064 *MovedAway = false;
4065
4066 switch (Opcode) {
4067 case Instruction::PtrToInt:
4068 // PtrToInt is always a noop, as we know that the int type is pointer sized.
4069 return matchAddr(AddrInst->getOperand(0), Depth);
4070 case Instruction::IntToPtr: {
4071 auto AS = AddrInst->getType()->getPointerAddressSpace();
4072 auto PtrTy = MVT::getIntegerVT(DL.getPointerSizeInBits(AS));
4073 // This inttoptr is a no-op if the integer type is pointer sized.
4074 if (TLI.getValueType(DL, AddrInst->getOperand(0)->getType()) == PtrTy)
4075 return matchAddr(AddrInst->getOperand(0), Depth);
4076 return false;
4077 }
4078 case Instruction::BitCast:
4079 // BitCast is always a noop, and we can handle it as long as it is
4080 // int->int or pointer->pointer (we don't want int<->fp or something).
4081 if (AddrInst->getOperand(0)->getType()->isIntOrPtrTy() &&
4082 // Don't touch identity bitcasts. These were probably put here by LSR,
4083 // and we don't want to mess around with them. Assume it knows what it
4084 // is doing.
4085 AddrInst->getOperand(0)->getType() != AddrInst->getType())
4086 return matchAddr(AddrInst->getOperand(0), Depth);
4087 return false;
4088 case Instruction::AddrSpaceCast: {
4089 unsigned SrcAS
4090 = AddrInst->getOperand(0)->getType()->getPointerAddressSpace();
4091 unsigned DestAS = AddrInst->getType()->getPointerAddressSpace();
4092 if (TLI.isNoopAddrSpaceCast(SrcAS, DestAS))
4093 return matchAddr(AddrInst->getOperand(0), Depth);
4094 return false;
4095 }
4096 case Instruction::Add: {
4097 // Check to see if we can merge in the RHS then the LHS. If so, we win.
4098 ExtAddrMode BackupAddrMode = AddrMode;
4099 unsigned OldSize = AddrModeInsts.size();
4100 // Start a transaction at this point.
4101 // The LHS may match but not the RHS.
4102 // Therefore, we need a higher level restoration point to undo partially
4103 // matched operation.
4104 TypePromotionTransaction::ConstRestorationPt LastKnownGood =
4105 TPT.getRestorationPoint();
4106
4107 AddrMode.InBounds = false;
4108 if (matchAddr(AddrInst->getOperand(1), Depth+1) &&
4109 matchAddr(AddrInst->getOperand(0), Depth+1))
4110 return true;
4111
4112 // Restore the old addr mode info.
4113 AddrMode = BackupAddrMode;
4114 AddrModeInsts.resize(OldSize);
4115 TPT.rollback(LastKnownGood);
4116
4117 // Otherwise this was over-aggressive. Try merging in the LHS then the RHS.
4118 if (matchAddr(AddrInst->getOperand(0), Depth+1) &&
4119 matchAddr(AddrInst->getOperand(1), Depth+1))
4120 return true;
4121
4122 // Otherwise we definitely can't merge the ADD in.
4123 AddrMode = BackupAddrMode;
4124 AddrModeInsts.resize(OldSize);
4125 TPT.rollback(LastKnownGood);
4126 break;
4127 }
4128 //case Instruction::Or:
4129 // TODO: We can handle "Or Val, Imm" iff this OR is equivalent to an ADD.
4130 //break;
4131 case Instruction::Mul:
4132 case Instruction::Shl: {
4133 // Can only handle X*C and X << C.
4134 AddrMode.InBounds = false;
4135 ConstantInt *RHS = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(AddrInst->getOperand(1));
4136 if (!RHS || RHS->getBitWidth() > 64)
4137 return false;
4138 int64_t Scale = RHS->getSExtValue();
4139 if (Opcode == Instruction::Shl)
4140 Scale = 1LL << Scale;
4141
4142 return matchScaledValue(AddrInst->getOperand(0), Scale, Depth);
4143 }
4144 case Instruction::GetElementPtr: {
4145 // Scan the GEP. We check it if it contains constant offsets and at most
4146 // one variable offset.
4147 int VariableOperand = -1;
4148 unsigned VariableScale = 0;
4149
4150 int64_t ConstantOffset = 0;
4151 gep_type_iterator GTI = gep_type_begin(AddrInst);
4152 for (unsigned i = 1, e = AddrInst->getNumOperands(); i != e; ++i, ++GTI) {
4153 if (StructType *STy = GTI.getStructTypeOrNull()) {
4154 const StructLayout *SL = DL.getStructLayout(STy);
4155 unsigned Idx =
4156 cast<ConstantInt>(AddrInst->getOperand(i))->getZExtValue();
4157 ConstantOffset += SL->getElementOffset(Idx);
4158 } else {
4159 uint64_t TypeSize = DL.getTypeAllocSize(GTI.getIndexedType());
4160 if (ConstantInt *CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(AddrInst->getOperand(i))) {
4161 const APInt &CVal = CI->getValue();
4162 if (CVal.getMinSignedBits() <= 64) {
4163 ConstantOffset += CVal.getSExtValue() * TypeSize;
4164 continue;
4165 }
4166 }
4167 if (TypeSize) { // Scales of zero don't do anything.
4168 // We only allow one variable index at the moment.
4169 if (VariableOperand != -1)
4170 return false;
4171
4172 // Remember the variable index.
4173 VariableOperand = i;
4174 VariableScale = TypeSize;
4175 }
4176 }
4177 }
4178
4179 // A common case is for the GEP to only do a constant offset. In this case,
4180 // just add it to the disp field and check validity.
4181 if (VariableOperand == -1) {
4182 AddrMode.BaseOffs += ConstantOffset;
4183 if (ConstantOffset == 0 ||
4184 TLI.isLegalAddressingMode(DL, AddrMode, AccessTy, AddrSpace)) {
4185 // Check to see if we can fold the base pointer in too.
4186 if (matchAddr(AddrInst->getOperand(0), Depth+1)) {
4187 if (!cast<GEPOperator>(AddrInst)->isInBounds())
4188 AddrMode.InBounds = false;
4189 return true;
4190 }
4191 } else if (EnableGEPOffsetSplit && isa<GetElementPtrInst>(AddrInst) &&
4192 TLI.shouldConsiderGEPOffsetSplit() && Depth == 0 &&
4193 ConstantOffset > 0) {
4194 // Record GEPs with non-zero offsets as candidates for splitting in the
4195 // event that the offset cannot fit into the r+i addressing mode.
4196 // Simple and common case that only one GEP is used in calculating the
4197 // address for the memory access.
4198 Value *Base = AddrInst->getOperand(0);
4199 auto *BaseI = dyn_cast<Instruction>(Base);
4200 auto *GEP = cast<GetElementPtrInst>(AddrInst);
4201 if (isa<Argument>(Base) || isa<GlobalValue>(Base) ||
4202 (BaseI && !isa<CastInst>(BaseI) &&
4203 !isa<GetElementPtrInst>(BaseI))) {
4204 // If the base is an instruction, make sure the GEP is not in the same
4205 // basic block as the base. If the base is an argument or global
4206 // value, make sure the GEP is not in the entry block. Otherwise,
4207 // instruction selection can undo the split. Also make sure the
4208 // parent block allows inserting non-PHI instructions before the
4209 // terminator.
4210 BasicBlock *Parent =
4211 BaseI ? BaseI->getParent() : &GEP->getFunction()->getEntryBlock();
4212 if (GEP->getParent() != Parent && !Parent->getTerminator()->isEHPad())
4213 LargeOffsetGEP = std::make_pair(GEP, ConstantOffset);
4214 }
4215 }
4216 AddrMode.BaseOffs -= ConstantOffset;
4217 return false;
4218 }
4219
4220 // Save the valid addressing mode in case we can't match.
4221 ExtAddrMode BackupAddrMode = AddrMode;
4222 unsigned OldSize = AddrModeInsts.size();
4223
4224 // See if the scale and offset amount is valid for this target.
4225 AddrMode.BaseOffs += ConstantOffset;
4226 if (!cast<GEPOperator>(AddrInst)->isInBounds())
4227 AddrMode.InBounds = false;
4228
4229 // Match the base operand of the GEP.
4230 if (!matchAddr(AddrInst->getOperand(0), Depth+1)) {
4231 // If it couldn't be matched, just stuff the value in a register.
4232 if (AddrMode.HasBaseReg) {
4233 AddrMode = BackupAddrMode;
4234 AddrModeInsts.resize(OldSize);
4235 return false;
4236 }
4237 AddrMode.HasBaseReg = true;
4238 AddrMode.BaseReg = AddrInst->getOperand(0);
4239 }
4240
4241 // Match the remaining variable portion of the GEP.
4242 if (!matchScaledValue(AddrInst->getOperand(VariableOperand), VariableScale,
4243 Depth)) {
4244 // If it couldn't be matched, try stuffing the base into a register
4245 // instead of matching it, and retrying the match of the scale.
4246 AddrMode = BackupAddrMode;
4247 AddrModeInsts.resize(OldSize);
4248 if (AddrMode.HasBaseReg)
4249 return false;
4250 AddrMode.HasBaseReg = true;
4251 AddrMode.BaseReg = AddrInst->getOperand(0);
4252 AddrMode.BaseOffs += ConstantOffset;
4253 if (!matchScaledValue(AddrInst->getOperand(VariableOperand),
4254 VariableScale, Depth)) {
4255 // If even that didn't work, bail.
4256 AddrMode = BackupAddrMode;
4257 AddrModeInsts.resize(OldSize);
4258 return false;
4259 }
4260 }
4261
4262 return true;
4263 }
4264 case Instruction::SExt:
4265 case Instruction::ZExt: {
4266 Instruction *Ext = dyn_cast<Instruction>(AddrInst);
4267 if (!Ext)
4268 return false;
4269
4270 // Try to move this ext out of the way of the addressing mode.
4271 // Ask for a method for doing so.
4272 TypePromotionHelper::Action TPH =
4273 TypePromotionHelper::getAction(Ext, InsertedInsts, TLI, PromotedInsts);
4274 if (!TPH)
4275 return false;
4276
4277 TypePromotionTransaction::ConstRestorationPt LastKnownGood =
4278 TPT.getRestorationPoint();
4279 unsigned CreatedInstsCost = 0;
4280 unsigned ExtCost = !TLI.isExtFree(Ext);
4281 Value *PromotedOperand =
4282 TPH(Ext, TPT, PromotedInsts, CreatedInstsCost, nullptr, nullptr, TLI);
4283 // SExt has been moved away.
4284 // Thus either it will be rematched later in the recursive calls or it is
4285 // gone. Anyway, we must not fold it into the addressing mode at this point.
4286 // E.g.,
4287 // op = add opnd, 1
4288 // idx = ext op
4289 // addr = gep base, idx
4290 // is now:
4291 // promotedOpnd = ext opnd <- no match here
4292 // op = promoted_add promotedOpnd, 1 <- match (later in recursive calls)
4293 // addr = gep base, op <- match
4294 if (MovedAway)
4295 *MovedAway = true;
4296
4297 assert(PromotedOperand &&
4298 "TypePromotionHelper should have filtered out those cases");
4299
4300 ExtAddrMode BackupAddrMode = AddrMode;
4301 unsigned OldSize = AddrModeInsts.size();
4302
4303 if (!matchAddr(PromotedOperand, Depth) ||
4304 // The total of the new cost is equal to the cost of the created
4305 // instructions.
4306 // The total of the old cost is equal to the cost of the extension plus
4307 // what we have saved in the addressing mode.
4308 !isPromotionProfitable(CreatedInstsCost,
4309 ExtCost + (AddrModeInsts.size() - OldSize),
4310 PromotedOperand)) {
4311 AddrMode = BackupAddrMode;
4312 AddrModeInsts.resize(OldSize);
4313 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Sign extension does not pay off: rollback\n");
