4314 TPT.rollback(LastKnownGood);
4315 return false;
4316 }
4317 return true;
4318 }
4319 }
4320 return false;
4321}
4322
4323/// If we can, try to add the value of 'Addr' into the current addressing mode.
4324/// If Addr can't be added to AddrMode this returns false and leaves AddrMode
4325/// unmodified. This assumes that Addr is either a pointer type or intptr_t
4326/// for the target.
4327///
4328bool AddressingModeMatcher::matchAddr(Value *Addr, unsigned Depth) {
4329 // Start a transaction at this point that we will rollback if the matching
4330 // fails.
4331 TypePromotionTransaction::ConstRestorationPt LastKnownGood =
4332 TPT.getRestorationPoint();
4333 if (ConstantInt *CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(Addr)) {
4334 // Fold in immediates if legal for the target.
4335 AddrMode.BaseOffs += CI->getSExtValue();
4336 if (TLI.isLegalAddressingMode(DL, AddrMode, AccessTy, AddrSpace))
4337 return true;
4338 AddrMode.BaseOffs -= CI->getSExtValue();
4339 } else if (GlobalValue *GV = dyn_cast<GlobalValue>(Addr)) {
4340 // If this is a global variable, try to fold it into the addressing mode.
4341 if (!AddrMode.BaseGV) {
4342 AddrMode.BaseGV = GV;
4343 if (TLI.isLegalAddressingMode(DL, AddrMode, AccessTy, AddrSpace))
4344 return true;
4345 AddrMode.BaseGV = nullptr;
4346 }
4347 } else if (Instruction *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(Addr)) {
4348 ExtAddrMode BackupAddrMode = AddrMode;
4349 unsigned OldSize = AddrModeInsts.size();
4350
4351 // Check to see if it is possible to fold this operation.
4352 bool MovedAway = false;
4353 if (matchOperationAddr(I, I->getOpcode(), Depth, &MovedAway)) {
4354 // This instruction may have been moved away. If so, there is nothing
4355 // to check here.
4356 if (MovedAway)
4357 return true;
4358 // Okay, it's possible to fold this. Check to see if it is actually
4359 // *profitable* to do so. We use a simple cost model to avoid increasing
4360 // register pressure too much.
4361 if (I->hasOneUse() ||
4362 isProfitableToFoldIntoAddressingMode(I, BackupAddrMode, AddrMode)) {
4363 AddrModeInsts.push_back(I);
4364 return true;
4365 }
4366
4367 // It isn't profitable to do this, roll back.
4368 //cerr << "NOT FOLDING: " << *I;
4369 AddrMode = BackupAddrMode;
4370 AddrModeInsts.resize(OldSize);
4371 TPT.rollback(LastKnownGood);
4372 }
4373 } else if (ConstantExpr *CE = dyn_cast<ConstantExpr>(Addr)) {
4374 if (matchOperationAddr(CE, CE->getOpcode(), Depth))
4375 return true;
4376 TPT.rollback(LastKnownGood);
4377 } else if (isa<ConstantPointerNull>(Addr)) {
4378 // Null pointer gets folded without affecting the addressing mode.
4379 return true;
4380 }
4381
4382 // Worse case, the target should support [reg] addressing modes. :)
4383 if (!AddrMode.HasBaseReg) {
4384 AddrMode.HasBaseReg = true;
4385 AddrMode.BaseReg = Addr;
4386 // Still check for legality in case the target supports [imm] but not [i+r].
4387 if (TLI.isLegalAddressingMode(DL, AddrMode, AccessTy, AddrSpace))
4388 return true;
4389 AddrMode.HasBaseReg = false;
4390 AddrMode.BaseReg = nullptr;
4391 }
4392
4393 // If the base register is already taken, see if we can do [r+r].
4394 if (AddrMode.Scale == 0) {
4395 AddrMode.Scale = 1;
4396 AddrMode.ScaledReg = Addr;
4397 if (TLI.isLegalAddressingMode(DL, AddrMode, AccessTy, AddrSpace))
4398 return true;
4399 AddrMode.Scale = 0;
4400 AddrMode.ScaledReg = nullptr;
4401 }
4402 // Couldn't match.
4403 TPT.rollback(LastKnownGood);
4404 return false;
4405}
4406
4407/// Check to see if all uses of OpVal by the specified inline asm call are due
4408/// to memory operands. If so, return true, otherwise return false.
4409static bool IsOperandAMemoryOperand(CallInst *CI, InlineAsm *IA, Value *OpVal,
4410 const TargetLowering &TLI,
4411 const TargetRegisterInfo &TRI) {
4412 const Function *F = CI->getFunction();
4413 TargetLowering::AsmOperandInfoVector TargetConstraints =
4414 TLI.ParseConstraints(F->getParent()->getDataLayout(), &TRI,
4415 ImmutableCallSite(CI));
4416
4417 for (unsigned i = 0, e = TargetConstraints.size(); i != e; ++i) {
4418 TargetLowering::AsmOperandInfo &OpInfo = TargetConstraints[i];
4419
4420 // Compute the constraint code and ConstraintType to use.
4421 TLI.ComputeConstraintToUse(OpInfo, SDValue());
4422
4423 // If this asm operand is our Value*, and if it isn't an indirect memory
4424 // operand, we can't fold it!
4425 if (OpInfo.CallOperandVal == OpVal &&
4426 (OpInfo.ConstraintType != TargetLowering::C_Memory ||
4427 !OpInfo.isIndirect))
4428 return false;
4429 }
4430
4431 return true;
4432}
4433
4434// Max number of memory uses to look at before aborting the search to conserve
4435// compile time.
4436static constexpr int MaxMemoryUsesToScan = 20;
4437
4438/// Recursively walk all the uses of I until we find a memory use.
4439/// If we find an obviously non-foldable instruction, return true.
4440/// Add the ultimately found memory instructions to MemoryUses.
4441static bool FindAllMemoryUses(
4442 Instruction *I,
4443 SmallVectorImpl<std::pair<Instruction *, unsigned>> &MemoryUses,
4444 SmallPtrSetImpl<Instruction *> &ConsideredInsts, const TargetLowering &TLI,
4445 const TargetRegisterInfo &TRI, int SeenInsts = 0) {
4446 // If we already considered this instruction, we're done.
4447 if (!ConsideredInsts.insert(I).second)
4448 return false;
4449
4450 // If this is an obviously unfoldable instruction, bail out.
4451 if (!MightBeFoldableInst(I))
4452 return true;
4453
4454 const bool OptSize = I->getFunction()->hasOptSize();
4455
4456 // Loop over all the uses, recursively processing them.
4457 for (Use &U : I->uses()) {
4458 // Conservatively return true if we're seeing a large number or a deep chain
4459 // of users. This avoids excessive compilation times in pathological cases.
4460 if (SeenInsts++ >= MaxMemoryUsesToScan)
4461 return true;
4462
4463 Instruction *UserI = cast<Instruction>(U.getUser());
4464 if (LoadInst *LI = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(UserI)) {
4465 MemoryUses.push_back(std::make_pair(LI, U.getOperandNo()));
4466 continue;
4467 }
4468
4469 if (StoreInst *SI = dyn_cast<StoreInst>(UserI)) {
4470 unsigned opNo = U.getOperandNo();
4471 if (opNo != StoreInst::getPointerOperandIndex())
4472 return true; // Storing addr, not into addr.
4473 MemoryUses.push_back(std::make_pair(SI, opNo));
4474 continue;
4475 }
4476
4477 if (AtomicRMWInst *RMW = dyn_cast<AtomicRMWInst>(UserI)) {
4478 unsigned opNo = U.getOperandNo();
4479 if (opNo != AtomicRMWInst::getPointerOperandIndex())
4480 return true; // Storing addr, not into addr.
4481 MemoryUses.push_back(std::make_pair(RMW, opNo));
4482 continue;
4483 }
4484
4485 if (AtomicCmpXchgInst *CmpX = dyn_cast<AtomicCmpXchgInst>(UserI)) {
4486 unsigned opNo = U.getOperandNo();
4487 if (opNo != AtomicCmpXchgInst::getPointerOperandIndex())
4488 return true; // Storing addr, not into addr.
4489 MemoryUses.push_back(std::make_pair(CmpX, opNo));
4490 continue;
4491 }
4492
4493 if (CallInst *CI = dyn_cast<CallInst>(UserI)) {
4494 // If this is a cold call, we can sink the addressing calculation into
4495 // the cold path. See optimizeCallInst
4496 if (!OptSize && CI->hasFnAttr(Attribute::Cold))
4497 continue;
4498
4499 InlineAsm *IA = dyn_cast<InlineAsm>(CI->getCalledValue());
4500 if (!IA) return true;
4501
4502 // If this is a memory operand, we're cool, otherwise bail out.
4503 if (!IsOperandAMemoryOperand(CI, IA, I, TLI, TRI))
4504 return true;
4505 continue;
4506 }
4507
4508 if (FindAllMemoryUses(UserI, MemoryUses, ConsideredInsts, TLI, TRI,
4509 SeenInsts))
4510 return true;
4511 }
4512
4513 return false;
4514}
4515
4516/// Return true if Val is already known to be live at the use site that we're
4517/// folding it into. If so, there is no cost to include it in the addressing
4518/// mode. KnownLive1 and KnownLive2 are two values that we know are live at the
4519/// instruction already.
4520bool AddressingModeMatcher::valueAlreadyLiveAtInst(Value *Val,Value *KnownLive1,
4521 Value *KnownLive2) {
4522 // If Val is either of the known-live values, we know it is live!
4523 if (Val == nullptr || Val == KnownLive1 || Val == KnownLive2)
4524 return true;
4525
4526 // All values other than instructions and arguments (e.g. constants) are live.
4527 if (!isa<Instruction>(Val) && !isa<Argument>(Val)) return true;
4528
4529 // If Val is a constant sized alloca in the entry block, it is live, this is
4530 // true because it is just a reference to the stack/frame pointer, which is
4531 // live for the whole function.
4532 if (AllocaInst *AI = dyn_cast<AllocaInst>(Val))
4533 if (AI->isStaticAlloca())
4534 return true;
4535
4536 // Check to see if this value is already used in the memory instruction's
4537 // block. If so, it's already live into the block at the very least, so we
4538 // can reasonably fold it.
4539 return Val->isUsedInBasicBlock(MemoryInst->getParent());
4540}
4541
4542/// It is possible for the addressing mode of the machine to fold the specified
4543/// instruction into a load or store that ultimately uses it.
4544/// However, the specified instruction has multiple uses.
4545/// Given this, it may actually increase register pressure to fold it
4546/// into the load. For example, consider this code:
4547///
4548/// X = ...
4549/// Y = X+1
4550/// use(Y) -> nonload/store
4551/// Z = Y+1
4552/// load Z
4553///
4554/// In this case, Y has multiple uses, and can be folded into the load of Z
4555/// (yielding load [X+2]). However, doing this will cause both "X" and "X+1" to
4556/// be live at the use(Y) line. If we don't fold Y into load Z, we use one
4557/// fewer register. Since Y can't be folded into "use(Y)" we don't increase the
4558/// number of computations either.
4559///
4560/// Note that this (like most of CodeGenPrepare) is just a rough heuristic. If
4561/// X was live across 'load Z' for other reasons, we actually *would* want to
4562/// fold the addressing mode in the Z case. This would make Y die earlier.
4563bool AddressingModeMatcher::
4564isProfitableToFoldIntoAddressingMode(Instruction *I, ExtAddrMode &AMBefore,
4565 ExtAddrMode &AMAfter) {
4566 if (IgnoreProfitability) return true;
4567
4568 // AMBefore is the addressing mode before this instruction was folded into it,
4569 // and AMAfter is the addressing mode after the instruction was folded. Get
4570 // the set of registers referenced by AMAfter and subtract out those
4571 // referenced by AMBefore: this is the set of values which folding in this
4572 // address extends the lifetime of.
4573 //
4574 // Note that there are only two potential values being referenced here,
4575 // BaseReg and ScaleReg (global addresses are always available, as are any
4576 // folded immediates).
4577 Value *BaseReg = AMAfter.BaseReg, *ScaledReg = AMAfter.ScaledReg;
4578
4579 // If the BaseReg or ScaledReg was referenced by the previous addrmode, their
4580 // lifetime wasn't extended by adding this instruction.
4581 if (valueAlreadyLiveAtInst(BaseReg, AMBefore.BaseReg, AMBefore.ScaledReg))
4582 BaseReg = nullptr;
4583 if (valueAlreadyLiveAtInst(ScaledReg, AMBefore.BaseReg, AMBefore.ScaledReg))
4584 ScaledReg = nullptr;
4585
4586 // If folding this instruction (and it's subexprs) didn't extend any live
4587 // ranges, we're ok with it.
4588 if (!BaseReg && !ScaledReg)
4589 return true;
4590
4591 // If all uses of this instruction can have the address mode sunk into them,
4592 // we can remove the addressing mode and effectively trade one live register
4593 // for another (at worst.) In this context, folding an addressing mode into
4594 // the use is just a particularly nice way of sinking it.
4595 SmallVector<std::pair<Instruction*,unsigned>, 16> MemoryUses;
4596 SmallPtrSet<Instruction*, 16> ConsideredInsts;
4597 if (FindAllMemoryUses(I, MemoryUses, ConsideredInsts, TLI, TRI))
4598 return false; // Has a non-memory, non-foldable use!
4599
4600 // Now that we know that all uses of this instruction are part of a chain of
4601 // computation involving only operations that could theoretically be folded
4602 // into a memory use, loop over each of these memory operation uses and see
4603 // if they could *actually* fold the instruction. The assumption is that
4604 // addressing modes are cheap and that duplicating the computation involved
4605 // many times is worthwhile, even on a fastpath. For sinking candidates
4606 // (i.e. cold call sites), this serves as a way to prevent excessive code
4607 // growth since most architectures have some reasonable small and fast way to
4608 // compute an effective address. (i.e LEA on x86)
4609 SmallVector<Instruction*, 32> MatchedAddrModeInsts;
4610 for (unsigned i = 0, e = MemoryUses.size(); i != e; ++i) {
4611 Instruction *User = MemoryUses[i].first;
4612 unsigned OpNo = MemoryUses[i].second;
4613
4614 // Get the access type of this use. If the use isn't a pointer, we don't
4615 // know what it accesses.
4616 Value *Address = User->getOperand(OpNo);
4617 PointerType *AddrTy = dyn_cast<PointerType>(Address->getType());
4618 if (!AddrTy)
4619 return false;
4620 Type *AddressAccessTy = AddrTy->getElementType();
4621 unsigned AS = AddrTy->getAddressSpace();
4622
4623 // Do a match against the root of this address, ignoring profitability. This
4624 // will tell us if the addressing mode for the memory operation will
4625 // *actually* cover the shared instruction.
4626 ExtAddrMode Result;
4627 std::pair<AssertingVH<GetElementPtrInst>, int64_t> LargeOffsetGEP(nullptr,
4628 0);
4629 TypePromotionTransaction::ConstRestorationPt LastKnownGood =
4630 TPT.getRestorationPoint();
4631 AddressingModeMatcher Matcher(
4632 MatchedAddrModeInsts, TLI, TRI, AddressAccessTy, AS, MemoryInst, Result,
4633 InsertedInsts, PromotedInsts, TPT, LargeOffsetGEP);
4634 Matcher.IgnoreProfitability = true;
4635 bool Success = Matcher.matchAddr(Address, 0);
4636 (void)Success; assert(Success && "Couldn't select *anything*?");
4637
4638 // The match was to check the profitability, the changes made are not
4639 // part of the original matcher. Therefore, they should be dropped
4640 // otherwise the original matcher will not present the right state.
4641 TPT.rollback(LastKnownGood);
4642
4643 // If the match didn't cover I, then it won't be shared by it.
4644 if (!is_contained(MatchedAddrModeInsts, I))
4645 return false;
4646
4647 MatchedAddrModeInsts.clear();
4648 }
4649
4650 return true;
4651}
4652
4653/// Return true if the specified values are defined in a
4654/// different basic block than BB.
4655static bool IsNonLocalValue(Value *V, BasicBlock *BB) {
4656 if (Instruction *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(V))
4657 return I->getParent() != BB;
4658 return false;
4659}
4660
4661/// Sink addressing mode computation immediate before MemoryInst if doing so
4662/// can be done without increasing register pressure. The need for the
4663/// register pressure constraint means this can end up being an all or nothing
4664/// decision for all uses of the same addressing computation.
4665///
4666/// Load and Store Instructions often have addressing modes that can do
4667/// significant amounts of computation. As such, instruction selection will try
4668/// to get the load or store to do as much computation as possible for the
4669/// program. The problem is that isel can only see within a single block. As
4670/// such, we sink as much legal addressing mode work into the block as possible.
4671///
4672/// This method is used to optimize both load/store and inline asms with memory
4673/// operands. It's also used to sink addressing computations feeding into cold
4674/// call sites into their (cold) basic block.
4675///
4676/// The motivation for handling sinking into cold blocks is that doing so can
4677/// both enable other address mode sinking (by satisfying the register pressure
4678/// constraint above), and reduce register pressure globally (by removing the
4679/// addressing mode computation from the fast path entirely.).
4680bool CodeGenPrepare::optimizeMemoryInst(Instruction *MemoryInst, Value *Addr,
4681 Type *AccessTy, unsigned AddrSpace) {
4682 Value *Repl = Addr;
4683
4684 // Try to collapse single-value PHI nodes. This is necessary to undo
4685 // unprofitable PRE transformations.
4686 SmallVector<Value*, 8> worklist;
4687 SmallPtrSet<Value*, 16> Visited;
4688 worklist.push_back(Addr);
4689
4690 // Use a worklist to iteratively look through PHI and select nodes, and
4691 // ensure that the addressing mode obtained from the non-PHI/select roots of
4692 // the graph are compatible.
4693 bool PhiOrSelectSeen = false;
4694 SmallVector<Instruction*, 16> AddrModeInsts;
4695 const SimplifyQuery SQ(*DL, TLInfo);
4696 AddressingModeCombiner AddrModes(SQ, Addr);
4697 TypePromotionTransaction TPT(RemovedInsts);
4698 TypePromotionTransaction::ConstRestorationPt LastKnownGood =
4699 TPT.getRestorationPoint();
4700 while (!worklist.empty()) {
4701 Value *V = worklist.back();
4702 worklist.pop_back();
4703
4704 // We allow traversing cyclic Phi nodes.
4705 // In case of success after this loop we ensure that traversing through
4706 // Phi nodes ends up with all cases to compute address of the form
4707 // BaseGV + Base + Scale * Index + Offset
4708 // where Scale and Offset are constans and BaseGV, Base and Index
4709 // are exactly the same Values in all cases.
4710 // It means that BaseGV, Scale and Offset dominate our memory instruction
4711 // and have the same value as they had in address computation represented
4712 // as Phi. So we can safely sink address computation to memory instruction.
4713 if (!Visited.insert(V).second)
4714 continue;
4715
4716 // For a PHI node, push all of its incoming values.
4717 if (PHINode *P = dyn_cast<PHINode>(V)) {
4718 for (Value *IncValue : P->incoming_values())
4719 worklist.push_back(IncValue);
4720 PhiOrSelectSeen = true;
4721 continue;
4722 }
4723 // Similar for select.
4724 if (SelectInst *SI = dyn_cast<SelectInst>(V)) {
4725 worklist.push_back(SI->getFalseValue());
4726 worklist.push_back(SI->getTrueValue());
4727 PhiOrSelectSeen = true;
4728 continue;
4729 }
4730
4731 // For non-PHIs, determine the addressing mode being computed. Note that
4732 // the result may differ depending on what other uses our candidate
4733 // addressing instructions might have.
4734 AddrModeInsts.clear();
4735 std::pair<AssertingVH<GetElementPtrInst>, int64_t> LargeOffsetGEP(nullptr,
4736 0);
4737 ExtAddrMode NewAddrMode = AddressingModeMatcher::Match(
4738 V, AccessTy, AddrSpace, MemoryInst, AddrModeInsts, *TLI, *TRI,
4739 InsertedInsts, PromotedInsts, TPT, LargeOffsetGEP);
4740
4741 GetElementPtrInst *GEP = LargeOffsetGEP.first;
4742 if (GEP && GEP->getParent() != MemoryInst->getParent() &&
4743 !NewGEPBases.count(GEP)) {
4744 // If splitting the underlying data structure can reduce the offset of a
4745 // GEP, collect the GEP. Skip the GEPs that are the new bases of
4746 // previously split data structures.
4747 LargeOffsetGEPMap[GEP->getPointerOperand()].push_back(LargeOffsetGEP);
4748 if (LargeOffsetGEPID.find(GEP) == LargeOffsetGEPID.end())
4749 LargeOffsetGEPID[GEP] = LargeOffsetGEPID.size();
4750 }
4751
4752 NewAddrMode.OriginalValue = V;
4753 if (!AddrModes.addNewAddrMode(NewAddrMode))
4754 break;
4755 }
4756
4757 // Try to combine the AddrModes we've collected. If we couldn't collect any,
4758 // or we have multiple but either couldn't combine them or combining them
4759 // wouldn't do anything useful, bail out now.
4760 if (!AddrModes.combineAddrModes()) {
4761 TPT.rollback(LastKnownGood);
4762 return false;
4763 }
4764 TPT.commit();
4765
4766 // Get the combined AddrMode (or the only AddrMode, if we only had one).
4767 ExtAddrMode AddrMode = AddrModes.getAddrMode();
4768
4769 // If all the instructions matched are already in this BB, don't do anything.
4770 // If we saw a Phi node then it is not local definitely, and if we saw a select
4771 // then we want to push the address calculation past it even if it's already
4772 // in this BB.
4773 if (!PhiOrSelectSeen && none_of(AddrModeInsts, [&](Value *V) {
4774 return IsNonLocalValue(V, MemoryInst->getParent());
4775 })) {
4776 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "CGP: Found local addrmode: " << AddrMode
4777 << "\n");
4778 return false;
4779 }
4780
4781 // Insert this computation right after this user. Since our caller is
4782 // scanning from the top of the BB to the bottom, reuse of the expr are
4783 // guaranteed to happen later.
4784 IRBuilder<> Builder(MemoryInst);
4785
4786 // Now that we determined the addressing expression we want to use and know
4787 // that we have to sink it into this block. Check to see if we have already
4788 // done this for some other load/store instr in this block. If so, reuse
4789 // the computation. Before attempting reuse, check if the address is valid
4790 // as it may have been erased.
4791
4792 WeakTrackingVH SunkAddrVH = SunkAddrs[Addr];
4793
4794 Value * SunkAddr = SunkAddrVH.pointsToAliveValue() ? SunkAddrVH : nullptr;
4795 if (SunkAddr) {
4796 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "CGP: Reusing nonlocal addrmode: " << AddrMode
4797 << " for " << *MemoryInst << "\n");
4798 if (SunkAddr->getType() != Addr->getType())
4799 SunkAddr = Builder.CreatePointerCast(SunkAddr, Addr->getType());
4800 } else if (AddrSinkUsingGEPs ||
4801 (!AddrSinkUsingGEPs.getNumOccurrences() && TM && TTI->useAA())) {
4802 // By default, we use the GEP-based method when AA is used later. This
4803 // prevents new inttoptr/ptrtoint pairs from degrading AA capabilities.
4804 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "CGP: SINKING nonlocal addrmode: " << AddrMode
4805 << " for " << *MemoryInst << "\n");
4806 Type *IntPtrTy = DL->getIntPtrType(Addr->getType());
4807 Value *ResultPtr = nullptr, *ResultIndex = nullptr;
4808
4809 // First, find the pointer.
4810 if (AddrMode.BaseReg && AddrMode.BaseReg->getType()->isPointerTy()) {
4811 ResultPtr = AddrMode.BaseReg;
4812 AddrMode.BaseReg = nullptr;
4813 }
4814
4815 if (AddrMode.Scale && AddrMode.ScaledReg->getType()->isPointerTy()) {
4816 // We can't add more than one pointer together, nor can we scale a
4817 // pointer (both of which seem meaningless).
4818 if (ResultPtr || AddrMode.Scale != 1)
4819 return false;
4820
4821 ResultPtr = AddrMode.ScaledReg;
4822 AddrMode.Scale = 0;
4823 }
4824
4825 // It is only safe to sign extend the BaseReg if we know that the math
4826 // required to create it did not overflow before we extend it. Since
4827 // the original IR value was tossed in favor of a constant back when
4828 // the AddrMode was created we need to bail out gracefully if widths
4829 // do not match instead of extending it.
4830 //
4831 // (See below for code to add the scale.)
4832 if (AddrMode.Scale) {
4833 Type *ScaledRegTy = AddrMode.ScaledReg->getType();
4834 if (cast<IntegerType>(IntPtrTy)->getBitWidth() >
4835 cast<IntegerType>(ScaledRegTy)->getBitWidth())
4836 return false;
4837 }
4838
4839 if (AddrMode.BaseGV) {
4840 if (ResultPtr)
4841 return false;
4842
4843 ResultPtr = AddrMode.BaseGV;
4844 }
4845
4846 // If the real base value actually came from an inttoptr, then the matcher
4847 // will look through it and provide only the integer value. In that case,
4848 // use it here.
4849 if (!DL->isNonIntegralPointerType(Addr->getType())) {
4850 if (!ResultPtr && AddrMode.BaseReg) {
4851 ResultPtr = Builder.CreateIntToPtr(AddrMode.BaseReg, Addr->getType(),
4852 "sunkaddr");
4853 AddrMode.BaseReg = nullptr;
4854 } else if (!ResultPtr && AddrMode.Scale == 1) {
4855 ResultPtr = Builder.CreateIntToPtr(AddrMode.ScaledReg, Addr->getType(),
4856 "sunkaddr");
4857 AddrMode.Scale = 0;
4858 }
4859 }
4860
4861 if (!ResultPtr &&
4862 !AddrMode.BaseReg && !AddrMode.Scale && !AddrMode.BaseOffs) {
4863 SunkAddr = Constant::getNullValue(Addr->getType());
4864 } else if (!ResultPtr) {
4865 return false;
4866 } else {
4867 Type *I8PtrTy =
4868 Builder.getInt8PtrTy(Addr->getType()->getPointerAddressSpace());
4869 Type *I8Ty = Builder.getInt8Ty();
4870
4871 // Start with the base register. Do this first so that subsequent address
4872 // matching finds it last, which will prevent it from trying to match it
4873 // as the scaled value in case it happens to be a mul. That would be
4874 // problematic if we've sunk a different mul for the scale, because then
4875 // we'd end up sinking both muls.
4876 if (AddrMode.BaseReg) {
4877 Value *V = AddrMode.BaseReg;
4878 if (V->getType() != IntPtrTy)
4879 V = Builder.CreateIntCast(V, IntPtrTy, /*isSigned=*/true, "sunkaddr");
4880
4881 ResultIndex = V;
4882 }
4883
4884 // Add the scale value.
4885 if (AddrMode.Scale) {
4886 Value *V = AddrMode.ScaledReg;
4887 if (V->getType() == IntPtrTy) {
4888 // done.
4889 } else {
4890 assert(cast<IntegerType>(IntPtrTy)->getBitWidth() <
4891 cast<IntegerType>(V->getType())->getBitWidth() &&
4892 "We can't transform if ScaledReg is too narrow");
4893 V = Builder.CreateTrunc(V, IntPtrTy, "sunkaddr");
4894 }
4895
4896 if (AddrMode.Scale != 1)
4897 V = Builder.CreateMul(V, ConstantInt::get(IntPtrTy, AddrMode.Scale),
4898 "sunkaddr");
4899 if (ResultIndex)
4900 ResultIndex = Builder.CreateAdd(ResultIndex, V, "sunkaddr");
4901 else
4902 ResultIndex = V;
4903 }
4904
4905 // Add in the Base Offset if present.
4906 if (AddrMode.BaseOffs) {
4907 Value *V = ConstantInt::get(IntPtrTy, AddrMode.BaseOffs);
4908 if (ResultIndex) {
4909 // We need to add this separately from the scale above to help with
4910 // SDAG consecutive load/store merging.
4911 if (ResultPtr->getType() != I8PtrTy)
4912 ResultPtr = Builder.CreatePointerBitCastOrAddrSpaceCast(ResultPtr, I8PtrTy);
4913 ResultPtr =
4914 AddrMode.InBounds
4915 ? Builder.CreateInBoundsGEP(I8Ty, ResultPtr, ResultIndex,
4916 "sunkaddr")
4917 : Builder.CreateGEP(I8Ty, ResultPtr, ResultIndex, "sunkaddr");
4918 }
4919
4920 ResultIndex = V;
4921 }
4922
4923 if (!ResultIndex) {
4924 SunkAddr = ResultPtr;
4925 } else {
4926 if (ResultPtr->getType() != I8PtrTy)
4927 ResultPtr = Builder.CreatePointerBitCastOrAddrSpaceCast(ResultPtr, I8PtrTy);
4928 SunkAddr =
4929 AddrMode.InBounds
4930 ? Builder.CreateInBoundsGEP(I8Ty, ResultPtr, ResultIndex,
4931 "sunkaddr")
4932 : Builder.CreateGEP(I8Ty, ResultPtr, ResultIndex, "sunkaddr");
4933 }
4934
4935 if (SunkAddr->getType() != Addr->getType())
4936 SunkAddr = Builder.CreatePointerBitCastOrAddrSpaceCast(SunkAddr, Addr->getType());
4937 }
4938 } else {
4939 // We'd require a ptrtoint/inttoptr down the line, which we can't do for
4940 // non-integral pointers, so in that case bail out now.
4941 Type *BaseTy = AddrMode.BaseReg ? AddrMode.BaseReg->getType() : nullptr;
4942 Type *ScaleTy = AddrMode.Scale ? AddrMode.ScaledReg->getType() : nullptr;
4943 PointerType *BasePtrTy = dyn_cast_or_null<PointerType>(BaseTy);
4944 PointerType *ScalePtrTy = dyn_cast_or_null<PointerType>(ScaleTy);
4945 if (DL->isNonIntegralPointerType(Addr->getType()) ||
4946 (BasePtrTy && DL->isNonIntegralPointerType(BasePtrTy)) ||
4947 (ScalePtrTy && DL->isNonIntegralPointerType(ScalePtrTy)) ||
4948 (AddrMode.BaseGV &&
4949 DL->isNonIntegralPointerType(AddrMode.BaseGV->getType())))
4950 return false;
4951
4952 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "CGP: SINKING nonlocal addrmode: " << AddrMode
4953 << " for " << *MemoryInst << "\n");
4954 Type *IntPtrTy = DL->getIntPtrType(Addr->getType());
4955 Value *Result = nullptr;
4956
4957 // Start with the base register. Do this first so that subsequent address
4958 // matching finds it last, which will prevent it from trying to match it
4959 // as the scaled value in case it happens to be a mul. That would be
4960 // problematic if we've sunk a different mul for the scale, because then
4961 // we'd end up sinking both muls.
4962 if (AddrMode.BaseReg) {
4963 Value *V = AddrMode.BaseReg;
4964 if (V->getType()->isPointerTy())
4965 V = Builder.CreatePtrToInt(V, IntPtrTy, "sunkaddr");
4966 if (V->getType() != IntPtrTy)
4967 V = Builder.CreateIntCast(V, IntPtrTy, /*isSigned=*/true, "sunkaddr");
4968 Result = V;
4969 }
4970
4971 // Add the scale value.
4972 if (AddrMode.Scale) {
4973 Value *V = AddrMode.ScaledReg;
4974 if (V->getType() == IntPtrTy) {
4975 // done.
4976 } else if (V->getType()->isPointerTy()) {
4977 V = Builder.CreatePtrToInt(V, IntPtrTy, "sunkaddr");
4978 } else if (cast<IntegerType>(IntPtrTy)->getBitWidth() <
4979 cast<IntegerType>(V->getType())->getBitWidth()) {
4980 V = Builder.CreateTrunc(V, IntPtrTy, "sunkaddr");
4981 } else {
4982 // It is only safe to sign extend the BaseReg if we know that the math
4983 // required to create it did not overflow before we extend it. Since
4984 // the original IR value was tossed in favor of a constant back when
4985 // the AddrMode was created we need to bail out gracefully if widths
4986 // do not match instead of extending it.
4987 Instruction *I = dyn_cast_or_null<Instruction>(Result);
4988 if (I && (Result != AddrMode.BaseReg))
4989 I->eraseFromParent();
4990 return false;
4991 }
4992 if (AddrMode.Scale != 1)
4993 V = Builder.CreateMul(V, ConstantInt::get(IntPtrTy, AddrMode.Scale),
4994 "sunkaddr");
4995 if (Result)
4996 Result = Builder.CreateAdd(Result, V, "sunkaddr");
4997 else
4998 Result = V;
4999 }
5000
5001 // Add in the BaseGV if present.
5002 if (AddrMode.BaseGV) {
5003 Value *V = Builder.CreatePtrToInt(AddrMode.BaseGV, IntPtrTy, "sunkaddr");
5004 if (Result)
5005 Result = Builder.CreateAdd(Result, V, "sunkaddr");
5006 else
5007 Result = V;
5008 }
5009
5010 // Add in the Base Offset if present.
5011 if (AddrMode.BaseOffs) {
5012 Value *V = ConstantInt::get(IntPtrTy, AddrMode.BaseOffs);
5013 if (Result)
5014 Result = Builder.CreateAdd(Result, V, "sunkaddr");
5015 else
5016 Result = V;
5017 }
5018
5019 if (!Result)
5020 SunkAddr = Constant::getNullValue(Addr->getType());
5021 else
5022 SunkAddr = Builder.CreateIntToPtr(Result, Addr->getType(), "sunkaddr");
5023 }
5024
5025 MemoryInst->replaceUsesOfWith(Repl, SunkAddr);
5026 // Store the newly computed address into the cache. In the case we reused a
5027 // value, this should be idempotent.
5028 SunkAddrs[Addr] = WeakTrackingVH(SunkAddr);
5029
5030 // If we have no uses, recursively delete the value and all dead instructions
5031 // using it.
5032 if (Repl->use_empty()) {
5033 // This can cause recursive deletion, which can invalidate our iterator.
5034 // Use a WeakTrackingVH to hold onto it in case this happens.
5035 Value *CurValue = &*CurInstIterator;
5036 WeakTrackingVH IterHandle(CurValue);
5037 BasicBlock *BB = CurInstIterator->getParent();
5038
5039 RecursivelyDeleteTriviallyDeadInstructions(Repl, TLInfo);
5040
5041 if (IterHandle != CurValue) {
5042 // If the iterator instruction was recursively deleted, start over at the
5043 // start of the block.
5044 CurInstIterator = BB->begin();
5045 SunkAddrs.clear();
5046 }
5047 }
5048 ++NumMemoryInsts;
5049 return true;
5050}
5051
5052/// If there are any memory operands, use OptimizeMemoryInst to sink their
5053/// address computing into the block when possible / profitable.
5054bool CodeGenPrepare::optimizeInlineAsmInst(CallInst *CS) {
5055 bool MadeChange = false;
5056
5057 const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI =
5058 TM->getSubtargetImpl(*CS->getFunction())->getRegisterInfo();
5059 TargetLowering::AsmOperandInfoVector TargetConstraints =
5060 TLI->ParseConstraints(*DL, TRI, CS);
5061 unsigned ArgNo = 0;
5062 for (unsigned i = 0, e = TargetConstraints.size(); i != e; ++i) {
5063 TargetLowering::AsmOperandInfo &OpInfo = TargetConstraints[i];
5064
5065 // Compute the constraint code and ConstraintType to use.
5066 TLI->ComputeConstraintToUse(OpInfo, SDValue());
5067
5068 if (OpInfo.ConstraintType == TargetLowering::C_Memory &&
5069 OpInfo.isIndirect) {
5070 Value *OpVal = CS->getArgOperand(ArgNo++);
5071 MadeChange |= optimizeMemoryInst(CS, OpVal, OpVal->getType(), ~0u);
5072 } else if (OpInfo.Type == InlineAsm::isInput)
5073 ArgNo++;
5074 }
5075
5076 return MadeChange;
5077}
5078
5079/// Check if all the uses of \p Val are equivalent (or free) zero or
5080/// sign extensions.
5081static bool hasSameExtUse(Value *Val, const TargetLowering &TLI) {
5082 assert(!Val->use_empty() && "Input must have at least one use");
5083 const Instruction *FirstUser = cast<Instruction>(*Val->user_begin());
5084 bool IsSExt = isa<SExtInst>(FirstUser);
5085 Type *ExtTy = FirstUser->getType();
5086 for (const User *U : Val->users()) {
5087 const Instruction *UI = cast<Instruction>(U);
5088 if ((IsSExt && !isa<SExtInst>(UI)) || (!IsSExt && !isa<ZExtInst>(UI)))
5089 return false;
5090 Type *CurTy = UI->getType();
5091 // Same input and output types: Same instruction after CSE.
5092 if (CurTy == ExtTy)
5093 continue;
5094
5095 // If IsSExt is true, we are in this situation:
5096 // a = Val
5097 // b = sext ty1 a to ty2
5098 // c = sext ty1 a to ty3
5099 // Assuming ty2 is shorter than ty3, this could be turned into:
5100 // a = Val
5101 // b = sext ty1 a to ty2
5102 // c = sext ty2 b to ty3
5103 // However, the last sext is not free.
5104 if (IsSExt)
5105 return false;
5106
5107 // This is a ZExt, maybe this is free to extend from one type to another.
5108 // In that case, we would not account for a different use.
5109 Type *NarrowTy;
5110 Type *LargeTy;
5111 if (ExtTy->getScalarType()->getIntegerBitWidth() >
5112 CurTy->getScalarType()->getIntegerBitWidth()) {
5113 NarrowTy = CurTy;
5114 LargeTy = ExtTy;
5115 } else {
5116 NarrowTy = ExtTy;
5117 LargeTy = CurTy;
5118 }
5119
5120 if (!TLI.isZExtFree(NarrowTy, LargeTy))
5121 return false;
5122 }
5123 // All uses are the same or can be derived from one another for free.
5124 return true;
5125}
5126
5127/// Try to speculatively promote extensions in \p Exts and continue
5128/// promoting through newly promoted operands recursively as far as doing so is
5129/// profitable. Save extensions profitably moved up, in \p ProfitablyMovedExts.
5130/// When some promotion happened, \p TPT contains the proper state to revert
5131/// them.
5132///
5133/// \return true if some promotion happened, false otherwise.
5134bool CodeGenPrepare::tryToPromoteExts(
5135 TypePromotionTransaction &TPT, const SmallVectorImpl<Instruction *> &Exts,
5136 SmallVectorImpl<Instruction *> &ProfitablyMovedExts,
5137 unsigned CreatedInstsCost) {
5138 bool Promoted = false;
5139
5140 // Iterate over all the extensions to try to promote them.
5141 for (auto I : Exts) {
5142 // Early check if we directly have ext(load).
5143 if (isa<LoadInst>(I->getOperand(0))) {
5144 ProfitablyMovedExts.push_back(I);
5145 continue;
5146 }
5147
5148 // Check whether or not we want to do any promotion. The reason we have
5149 // this check inside the for loop is to catch the case where an extension
5150 // is directly fed by a load because in such case the extension can be moved
5151 // up without any promotion on its operands.
5152 if (!TLI || !TLI->enableExtLdPromotion() || DisableExtLdPromotion)
5153 return false;
5154
5155 // Get the action to perform the promotion.
5156 TypePromotionHelper::Action TPH =
5157 TypePromotionHelper::getAction(I, InsertedInsts, *TLI, PromotedInsts);
5158 // Check if we can promote.
5159 if (!TPH) {
5160 // Save the current extension as we cannot move up through its operand.
5161 ProfitablyMovedExts.push_back(I);
5162 continue;
5163 }
5164
5165 // Save the current state.
5166 TypePromotionTransaction::ConstRestorationPt LastKnownGood =
5167 TPT.getRestorationPoint();
5168 SmallVector<Instruction *, 4> NewExts;
5169 unsigned NewCreatedInstsCost = 0;
5170 unsigned ExtCost = !TLI->isExtFree(I);
5171 // Promote.
5172 Value *PromotedVal = TPH(I, TPT, PromotedInsts, NewCreatedInstsCost,
5173 &NewExts, nullptr, *TLI);
5174 assert(PromotedVal &&
5175 "TypePromotionHelper should have filtered out those cases");
5176
5177 // We would be able to merge only one extension in a load.
5178 // Therefore, if we have more than 1 new extension we heuristically
5179 // cut this search path, because it means we degrade the code quality.
5180 // With exactly 2, the transformation is neutral, because we will merge
5181 // one extension but leave one. However, we optimistically keep going,
5182 // because the new extension may be removed too.
5183 long long TotalCreatedInstsCost = CreatedInstsCost + NewCreatedInstsCost;
5184 // FIXME: It would be possible to propagate a negative value instead of
5185 // conservatively ceiling it to 0.
5186 TotalCreatedInstsCost =
5187 std::max((long long)0, (TotalCreatedInstsCost - ExtCost));
5188 if (!StressExtLdPromotion &&
5189 (TotalCreatedInstsCost > 1 ||
5190 !isPromotedInstructionLegal(*TLI, *DL, PromotedVal))) {
5191 // This promotion is not profitable, rollback to the previous state, and
5192 // save the current extension in ProfitablyMovedExts as the latest
5193 // speculative promotion turned out to be unprofitable.
5194 TPT.rollback(LastKnownGood);
5195 ProfitablyMovedExts.push_back(I);
5196 continue;
5197 }
5198 // Continue promoting NewExts as far as doing so is profitable.
5199 SmallVector<Instruction *, 2> NewlyMovedExts;
5200 (void)tryToPromoteExts(TPT, NewExts, NewlyMovedExts, TotalCreatedInstsCost);
5201 bool NewPromoted = false;
5202 for (auto ExtInst : NewlyMovedExts) {
5203 Instruction *MovedExt = cast<Instruction>(ExtInst);
5204 Value *ExtOperand = MovedExt->getOperand(0);
5205 // If we have reached to a load, we need this extra profitability check
5206 // as it could potentially be merged into an ext(load).
5207 if (isa<LoadInst>(ExtOperand) &&
5208 !(StressExtLdPromotion || NewCreatedInstsCost <= ExtCost ||
5209 (ExtOperand->hasOneUse() || hasSameExtUse(ExtOperand, *TLI))))
5210 continue;
5211
5212 ProfitablyMovedExts.push_back(MovedExt);
5213 NewPromoted = true;
5214 }
5215
5216 // If none of speculative promotions for NewExts is profitable, rollback
5217 // and save the current extension (I) as the last profitable extension.
5218 if (!NewPromoted) {
5219 TPT.rollback(LastKnownGood);
5220 ProfitablyMovedExts.push_back(I);
5221 continue;
5222 }
5223 // The promotion is profitable.
5224 Promoted = true;
5225 }
5226 return Promoted;
5227}
5228
5229/// Merging redundant sexts when one is dominating the other.
5230bool CodeGenPrepare::mergeSExts(Function &F) {
5231 bool Changed = false;
5232 for (auto &Entry : ValToSExtendedUses) {
5233 SExts &Insts = Entry.second;
5234 SExts CurPts;
5235 for (Instruction *Inst : Insts) {
5236 if (RemovedInsts.count(Inst) || !isa<SExtInst>(Inst) ||
5237 Inst->getOperand(0) != Entry.first)
5238 continue;
5239 bool inserted = false;
5240 for (auto &Pt : CurPts) {
5241 if (getDT(F).dominates(Inst, Pt)) {
5242 Pt->replaceAllUsesWith(Inst);
5243 RemovedInsts.insert(Pt);
5244 Pt->removeFromParent();
5245 Pt = Inst;
5246 inserted = true;
5247 Changed = true;
5248 break;
5249 }
5250 if (!getDT(F).dominates(Pt, Inst))
5251 // Give up if we need to merge in a common dominator as the
5252 // experiments show it is not profitable.
5253 continue;
5254 Inst->replaceAllUsesWith(Pt);
5255 RemovedInsts.insert(Inst);
5256 Inst->removeFromParent();
5257 inserted = true;
5258 Changed = true;
5259 break;
5260 }
5261 if (!inserted)
5262 CurPts.push_back(Inst);
5263 }
5264 }
5265 return Changed;
5266}
5267
5268// Spliting large data structures so that the GEPs accessing them can have
5269// smaller offsets so that they can be sunk to the same blocks as their users.
5270// For example, a large struct starting from %base is splitted into two parts
5271// where the second part starts from %new_base.
5272//
5273// Before:
5274// BB0:
5275// %base =
5276//
5277// BB1:
5278// %gep0 = gep %base, off0
5279// %gep1 = gep %base, off1
5280// %gep2 = gep %base, off2
5281//
5282// BB2:
5283// %load1 = load %gep0
5284// %load2 = load %gep1
5285// %load3 = load %gep2
5286//
5287// After:
5288// BB0:
5289// %base =
5290// %new_base = gep %base, off0
5291//
5292// BB1:
5293// %new_gep0 = %new_base
5294// %new_gep1 = gep %new_base, off1 - off0
5295// %new_gep2 = gep %new_base, off2 - off0
5296//
5297// BB2:
5298// %load1 = load i32, i32* %new_gep0
5299// %load2 = load i32, i32* %new_gep1
5300// %load3 = load i32, i32* %new_gep2
5301//
5302// %new_gep1 and %new_gep2 can be sunk to BB2 now after the splitting because
5303// their offsets are smaller enough to fit into the addressing mode.
5304bool CodeGenPrepare::splitLargeGEPOffsets() {
5305 bool Changed = false;
5306 for (auto &Entry : LargeOffsetGEPMap) {
5307 Value *OldBase = Entry.first;
5308 SmallVectorImpl<std::pair<AssertingVH<GetElementPtrInst>, int64_t>>
5309 &LargeOffsetGEPs = Entry.second;
5310 auto compareGEPOffset =
5311 [&](const std::pair<GetElementPtrInst *, int64_t> &LHS,
5312 const std::pair<GetElementPtrInst *, int64_t> &RHS) {
5313 if (LHS.first == RHS.first)
5314 return false;
5315 if (LHS.second != RHS.second)
5316 return LHS.second < RHS.second;
5317 return LargeOffsetGEPID[LHS.first] < LargeOffsetGEPID[RHS.first];
5318 };
5319 // Sorting all the GEPs of the same data structures based on the offsets.
5320 llvm::sort(LargeOffsetGEPs, compareGEPOffset);
5321 LargeOffsetGEPs.erase(
5322 std::unique(LargeOffsetGEPs.begin(), LargeOffsetGEPs.end()),
5323 LargeOffsetGEPs.end());
5324 // Skip if all the GEPs have the same offsets.
5325 if (LargeOffsetGEPs.front().second == LargeOffsetGEPs.back().second)
5326 continue;
5327 GetElementPtrInst *BaseGEP = LargeOffsetGEPs.begin()->first;
5328 int64_t BaseOffset = LargeOffsetGEPs.begin()->second;
5329 Value *NewBaseGEP = nullptr;
5330
5331 auto LargeOffsetGEP = LargeOffsetGEPs.begin();
5332 while (LargeOffsetGEP != LargeOffsetGEPs.end()) {
5333 GetElementPtrInst *GEP = LargeOffsetGEP->first;
5334 int64_t Offset = LargeOffsetGEP->second;
5335 if (Offset != BaseOffset) {
5336 TargetLowering::AddrMode AddrMode;
5337 AddrMode.BaseOffs = Offset - BaseOffset;
5338 // The result type of the GEP might not be the type of the memory
5339 // access.
5340 if (!TLI->isLegalAddressingMode(*DL, AddrMode,
5341 GEP->getResultElementType(),
5342 GEP->getAddressSpace())) {
5343 // We need to create a new base if the offset to the current base is
5344 // too large to fit into the addressing mode. So, a very large struct
5345 // may be splitted into several parts.
5346 BaseGEP = GEP;
5347 BaseOffset = Offset;
5348 NewBaseGEP = nullptr;
5349 }
5350 }
5351
5352 // Generate a new GEP to replace the current one.
5353 LLVMContext &Ctx = GEP->getContext();
5354 Type *IntPtrTy = DL->getIntPtrType(GEP->getType());
5355 Type *I8PtrTy =
5356 Type::getInt8PtrTy(Ctx, GEP->getType()->getPointerAddressSpace());
5357 Type *I8Ty = Type::getInt8Ty(Ctx);
5358
5359 if (!NewBaseGEP) {
5360 // Create a new base if we don't have one yet. Find the insertion
5361 // pointer for the new base first.
5362 BasicBlock::iterator NewBaseInsertPt;
5363 BasicBlock *NewBaseInsertBB;
5364 if (auto *BaseI = dyn_cast<Instruction>(OldBase)) {
5365 // If the base of the struct is an instruction, the new base will be
5366 // inserted close to it.
5367 NewBaseInsertBB = BaseI->getParent();
5368 if (isa<PHINode>(BaseI))
5369 NewBaseInsertPt = NewBaseInsertBB->getFirstInsertionPt();
5370 else if (InvokeInst *Invoke = dyn_cast<InvokeInst>(BaseI)) {
5371 NewBaseInsertBB =
5372 SplitEdge(NewBaseInsertBB, Invoke->getNormalDest());
5373 NewBaseInsertPt = NewBaseInsertBB->getFirstInsertionPt();
5374 } else
5375 NewBaseInsertPt = std::next(BaseI->getIterator());
5376 } else {
5377 // If the current base is an argument or global value, the new base
5378 // will be inserted to the entry block.
5379 NewBaseInsertBB = &BaseGEP->getFunction()->getEntryBlock();
5380 NewBaseInsertPt = NewBaseInsertBB->getFirstInsertionPt();
5381 }
5382 IRBuilder<> NewBaseBuilder(NewBaseInsertBB, NewBaseInsertPt);
5383 // Create a new base.
5384 Value *BaseIndex = ConstantInt::get(IntPtrTy, BaseOffset);
5385 NewBaseGEP = OldBase;
5386 if (NewBaseGEP->getType() != I8PtrTy)
5387 NewBaseGEP = NewBaseBuilder.CreatePointerCast(NewBaseGEP, I8PtrTy);
5388 NewBaseGEP =
5389 NewBaseBuilder.CreateGEP(I8Ty, NewBaseGEP, BaseIndex, "splitgep");
5390 NewGEPBases.insert(NewBaseGEP);
5391 }
5392
5393 IRBuilder<> Builder(GEP);
5394 Value *NewGEP = NewBaseGEP;
5395 if (Offset == BaseOffset) {
5396 if (GEP->getType() != I8PtrTy)
5397 NewGEP = Builder.CreatePointerCast(NewGEP, GEP->getType());
5398 } else {
5399 // Calculate the new offset for the new GEP.
5400 Value *Index = ConstantInt::get(IntPtrTy, Offset - BaseOffset);
5401 NewGEP = Builder.CreateGEP(I8Ty, NewBaseGEP, Index);
5402
5403 if (GEP->getType() != I8PtrTy)
5404 NewGEP = Builder.CreatePointerCast(NewGEP, GEP->getType());
5405 }
5406 GEP->replaceAllUsesWith(NewGEP);
5407 LargeOffsetGEPID.erase(GEP);
5408 LargeOffsetGEP = LargeOffsetGEPs.erase(LargeOffsetGEP);
5409 GEP->eraseFromParent();
5410 Changed = true;
5411 }
5412 }
5413 return Changed;
5414}
5415
5416/// Return true, if an ext(load) can be formed from an extension in
5417/// \p MovedExts.
5418bool CodeGenPrepare::canFormExtLd(
5419 const SmallVectorImpl<Instruction *> &MovedExts, LoadInst *&LI,
5420 Instruction *&Inst, bool HasPromoted) {
5421 for (auto *MovedExtInst : MovedExts) {
5422 if (isa<LoadInst>(MovedExtInst->getOperand(0))) {
5423 LI = cast<LoadInst>(MovedExtInst->getOperand(0));
5424 Inst = MovedExtInst;
5425 break;
5426 }
5427 }
5428 if (!LI)
5429 return false;
5430
5431 // If they're already in the same block, there's nothing to do.
5432 // Make the cheap checks first if we did not promote.
5433 // If we promoted, we need to check if it is indeed profitable.
5434 if (!HasPromoted && LI->getParent() == Inst->getParent())
5435 return false;
5436
5437 return TLI->isExtLoad(LI, Inst, *DL);
5438}
5439
5440/// Move a zext or sext fed by a load into the same basic block as the load,
5441/// unless conditions are unfavorable. This allows SelectionDAG to fold the
5442/// extend into the load.
5443///
5444/// E.g.,
5445/// \code
5446/// %ld = load i32* %addr
5447/// %add = add nuw i32 %ld, 4
5448/// %zext = zext i32 %add to i64
5449// \endcode
5450/// =>
5451/// \code
5452/// %ld = load i32* %addr
5453/// %zext = zext i32 %ld to i64
5454/// %add = add nuw i64 %zext, 4
5455/// \encode
5456/// Note that the promotion in %add to i64 is done in tryToPromoteExts(), which
5457/// allow us to match zext(load i32*) to i64.
5458///
5459/// Also, try to promote the computations used to obtain a sign extended
5460/// value used into memory accesses.
5461/// E.g.,
5462/// \code
5463/// a = add nsw i32 b, 3
5464/// d = sext i32 a to i64
5465/// e = getelementptr ..., i64 d
5466/// \endcode
5467/// =>
5468/// \code
5469/// f = sext i32 b to i64
5470/// a = add nsw i64 f, 3
5471/// e = getelementptr ..., i64 a
5472/// \endcode
5473///
5474/// \p Inst[in/out] the extension may be modified during the process if some
5475/// promotions apply.
5476bool CodeGenPrepare::optimizeExt(Instruction *&Inst) {
5477 // ExtLoad formation and address type promotion infrastructure requires TLI to
5478 // be effective.
5479 if (!TLI)
5480 return false;
5481
5482 bool AllowPromotionWithoutCommonHeader = false;
5483 /// See if it is an interesting sext operations for the address type
5484 /// promotion before trying to promote it, e.g., the ones with the right
5485 /// type and used in memory accesses.
5486 bool ATPConsiderable = TTI->shouldConsiderAddressTypePromotion(
5487 *Inst, AllowPromotionWithoutCommonHeader);
5488 TypePromotionTransaction TPT(RemovedInsts);
5489 TypePromotionTransaction::ConstRestorationPt LastKnownGood =
5490 TPT.getRestorationPoint();
5491 SmallVector<Instruction *, 1> Exts;
5492 SmallVector<Instruction *, 2> SpeculativelyMovedExts;
5493 Exts.push_back(Inst);
5494
5495 bool HasPromoted = tryToPromoteExts(TPT, Exts, SpeculativelyMovedExts);
5496
5497 // Look for a load being extended.
5498 LoadInst *LI = nullptr;
5499 Instruction *ExtFedByLoad;
5500
5501 // Try to promote a chain of computation if it allows to form an extended
5502 // load.
5503 if (canFormExtLd(SpeculativelyMovedExts, LI, ExtFedByLoad, HasPromoted)) {
5504 assert(LI && ExtFedByLoad && "Expect a valid load and extension");
5505 TPT.commit();
5506 // Move the extend into the same block as the load
5507 ExtFedByLoad->moveAfter(LI);
5508 // CGP does not check if the zext would be speculatively executed when moved
5509 // to the same basic block as the load. Preserving its original location
5510 // would pessimize the debugging experience, as well as negatively impact
5511 // the quality of sample pgo. We don't want to use "line 0" as that has a
5512 // size cost in the line-table section and logically the zext can be seen as
5513 // part of the load. Therefore we conservatively reuse the same debug
5514 // location for the load and the zext.
5515 ExtFedByLoad->setDebugLoc(LI->getDebugLoc());
5516 ++NumExtsMoved;
5517 Inst = ExtFedByLoad;
5518 return true;
5519 }
5520
5521 // Continue promoting SExts if known as considerable depending on targets.
5522 if (ATPConsiderable &&
5523 performAddressTypePromotion(Inst, AllowPromotionWithoutCommonHeader,
5524 HasPromoted, TPT, SpeculativelyMovedExts))
5525 return true;
5526
5527 TPT.rollback(LastKnownGood);
5528 return false;
5529}
5530
5531// Perform address type promotion if doing so is profitable.
5532// If AllowPromotionWithoutCommonHeader == false, we should find other sext
5533// instructions that sign extended the same initial value. However, if
5534// AllowPromotionWithoutCommonHeader == true, we expect promoting the
5535// extension is just profitable.
5536bool CodeGenPrepare::performAddressTypePromotion(
5537 Instruction *&Inst, bool AllowPromotionWithoutCommonHeader,
5538 bool HasPromoted, TypePromotionTransaction &TPT,
5539 SmallVectorImpl<Instruction *> &SpeculativelyMovedExts) {
5540 bool Promoted = false;
5541 SmallPtrSet<Instruction *, 1> UnhandledExts;
5542 bool AllSeenFirst = true;
5543 for (auto I : SpeculativelyMovedExts) {
5544 Value *HeadOfChain = I->getOperand(0);
5545 DenseMap<Value *, Instruction *>::iterator AlreadySeen =
5546 SeenChainsForSExt.find(HeadOfChain);
5547 // If there is an unhandled SExt which has the same header, try to promote
5548 // it as well.
5549 if (AlreadySeen != SeenChainsForSExt.end()) {
5550 if (AlreadySeen->second != nullptr)
5551 UnhandledExts.insert(AlreadySeen->second);
5552 AllSeenFirst = false;
5553 }
5554 }
5555
5556 if (!AllSeenFirst || (AllowPromotionWithoutCommonHeader &&
5557 SpeculativelyMovedExts.size() == 1)) {
5558 TPT.commit();
5559 if (HasPromoted)
5560 Promoted = true;
5561 for (auto I : SpeculativelyMovedExts) {
5562 Value *HeadOfChain = I->getOperand(0);
5563 SeenChainsForSExt[HeadOfChain] = nullptr;
5564 ValToSExtendedUses[HeadOfChain].push_back(I);
5565 }
5566 // Update Inst as promotion happen.
5567 Inst = SpeculativelyMovedExts.pop_back_val();
5568 } else {
5569 // This is the first chain visited from the header, keep the current chain
5570 // as unhandled. Defer to promote this until we encounter another SExt
5571 // chain derived from the same header.
5572 for (auto I : SpeculativelyMovedExts) {
5573 Value *HeadOfChain = I->getOperand(0);
5574 SeenChainsForSExt[HeadOfChain] = Inst;
5575 }
5576 return false;
5577 }
5578
5579 if (!AllSeenFirst && !UnhandledExts.empty())
5580 for (auto VisitedSExt : UnhandledExts) {
5581 if (RemovedInsts.count(VisitedSExt))
5582 continue;
5583 TypePromotionTransaction TPT(RemovedInsts);
5584 SmallVector<Instruction *, 1> Exts;
5585 SmallVector<Instruction *, 2> Chains;
5586 Exts.push_back(VisitedSExt);
5587 bool HasPromoted = tryToPromoteExts(TPT, Exts, Chains);
5588 TPT.commit();
5589 if (HasPromoted)
5590 Promoted = true;
5591 for (auto I : Chains) {
5592 Value *HeadOfChain = I->getOperand(0);
5593 // Mark this as handled.
5594 SeenChainsForSExt[HeadOfChain] = nullptr;
5595 ValToSExtendedUses[HeadOfChain].push_back(I);
5596 }
5597 }
5598 return Promoted;
5599}
5600
5601bool CodeGenPrepare::optimizeExtUses(Instruction *I) {
5602 BasicBlock *DefBB = I->getParent();
5603
5604 // If the result of a {s|z}ext and its source are both live out, rewrite all
5605 // other uses of the source with result of extension.
5606 Value *Src = I->getOperand(0);
5607 if (Src->hasOneUse())
5608 return false;
5609
5610 // Only do this xform if truncating is free.
5611 if (TLI && !TLI->isTruncateFree(I->getType(), Src->getType()))
5612 return false;
5613
5614 // Only safe to perform the optimization if the source is also defined in
5615 // this block.
5616 if (!isa<Instruction>(Src) || DefBB != cast<Instruction>(Src)->getParent())
5617 return false;
5618
5619 bool DefIsLiveOut = false;
5620 for (User *U : I->users()) {
5621 Instruction *UI = cast<Instruction>(U);
5622
5623 // Figure out which BB this ext is used in.
5624 BasicBlock *UserBB = UI->getParent();
5625 if (UserBB == DefBB) continue;
5626 DefIsLiveOut = true;
5627 break;
5628 }
5629 if (!DefIsLiveOut)
5630 return false;
5631
5632 // Make sure none of the uses are PHI nodes.
5633 for (User *U : Src->users()) {
5634 Instruction *UI = cast<Instruction>(U);
5635 BasicBlock *UserBB = UI->getParent();
5636 if (UserBB == DefBB) continue;
5637 // Be conservative. We don't want this xform to end up introducing
5638 // reloads just before load / store instructions.
5639 if (isa<PHINode>(UI) || isa<LoadInst>(UI) || isa<StoreInst>(UI))
5640 return false;
5641 }
5642
5643 // InsertedTruncs - Only insert one trunc in each block once.
5644 DenseMap<BasicBlock*, Instruction*> InsertedTruncs;
5645
5646 bool MadeChange = false;
5647 for (Use &U : Src->uses()) {
5648 Instruction *User = cast<Instruction>(U.getUser());
5649
5650 // Figure out which BB this ext is used in.
5651 BasicBlock *UserBB = User->getParent();
5652 if (UserBB == DefBB) continue;
5653
5654 // Both src and def are live in this block. Rewrite the use.
5655 Instruction *&InsertedTrunc = InsertedTruncs[UserBB];
5656
5657 if (!InsertedTrunc) {
5658 BasicBlock::iterator InsertPt = UserBB->getFirstInsertionPt();
5659 assert(InsertPt != UserBB->end());
5660 InsertedTrunc = new TruncInst(I, Src->getType(), "", &*InsertPt);
5661 InsertedInsts.insert(InsertedTrunc);
5662 }
5663
5664 // Replace a use of the {s|z}ext source with a use of the result.
5665 U = InsertedTrunc;
5666 ++NumExtUses;
5667 MadeChange = true;
5668 }
5669
5670 return MadeChange;
5671}
5672
5673// Find loads whose uses only use some of the loaded value's bits. Add an "and"
5674// just after the load if the target can fold this into one extload instruction,
5675// with the hope of eliminating some of the other later "and" instructions using
5676// the loaded value. "and"s that are made trivially redundant by the insertion
5677// of the new "and" are removed by this function, while others (e.g. those whose
5678// path from the load goes through a phi) are left for isel to potentially
5679// remove.
5680//
5681// For example:
5682//
5683// b0:
5684// x = load i32
5685// ...
5686// b1:
5687// y = and x, 0xff
5688// z = use y
5689//
5690// becomes:
5691//
5692// b0:
5693// x = load i32
5694// x' = and x, 0xff
5695// ...
5696// b1:
5697// z = use x'
5698//
5699// whereas:
5700//
5701// b0:
5702// x1 = load i32
5703// ...
5704// b1:
5705// x2 = load i32
5706// ...
5707// b2:
5708// x = phi x1, x2
5709// y = and x, 0xff
5710//
5711// becomes (after a call to optimizeLoadExt for each load):
5712//
5713// b0:
5714// x1 = load i32
5715// x1' = and x1, 0xff
5716// ...
5717// b1:
5718// x2 = load i32
5719// x2' = and x2, 0xff
5720// ...
5721// b2:
5722// x = phi x1', x2'
5723// y = and x, 0xff
5724bool CodeGenPrepare::optimizeLoadExt(LoadInst *Load) {
5725 if (!Load->isSimple() || !Load->getType()->isIntOrPtrTy())
5726 return false;
5727
5728 // Skip loads we've already transformed.
5729 if (Load->hasOneUse() &&
5730 InsertedInsts.count(cast<Instruction>(*Load->user_begin())))
5731 return false;
5732
5733 // Look at all uses of Load, looking through phis, to determine how many bits
5734 // of the loaded value are needed.
5735 SmallVector<Instruction *, 8> WorkList;
5736 SmallPtrSet<Instruction *, 16> Visited;
5737 SmallVector<Instruction *, 8> AndsToMaybeRemove;
5738 for (auto *U : Load->users())
5739 WorkList.push_back(cast<Instruction>(U));
5740
5741 EVT LoadResultVT = TLI->getValueType(*DL, Load->getType());
5742 unsigned BitWidth = LoadResultVT.getSizeInBits();
5743 APInt DemandBits(BitWidth, 0);
5744 APInt WidestAndBits(BitWidth, 0);
5745
5746 while (!WorkList.empty()) {
5747 Instruction *I = WorkList.back();
5748 WorkList.pop_back();
5749
5750 // Break use-def graph loops.
5751 if (!Visited.insert(I).second)
5752 continue;
5753
5754 // For a PHI node, push all of its users.
5755 if (auto *Phi = dyn_cast<PHINode>(I)) {
5756 for (auto *U : Phi->users())
5757 WorkList.push_back(cast<Instruction>(U));
5758 continue;
5759 }
5760
5761 switch (I->getOpcode()) {
5762 case Instruction::And: {
5763 auto *AndC = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(I->getOperand(1));
5764 if (!AndC)
5765 return false;
5766 APInt AndBits = AndC->getValue();
5767 DemandBits |= AndBits;
5768 // Keep track of the widest and mask we see.
5769 if (AndBits.ugt(WidestAndBits))
5770 WidestAndBits = AndBits;
5771 if (AndBits == WidestAndBits && I->getOperand(0) == Load)
5772 AndsToMaybeRemove.push_back(I);
5773 break;
5774 }
5775
5776 case Instruction::Shl: {
5777 auto *ShlC = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(I->getOperand(1));
5778 if (!ShlC)
5779 return false;
5780 uint64_t ShiftAmt = ShlC->getLimitedValue(BitWidth - 1);
5781 DemandBits.setLowBits(BitWidth - ShiftAmt);
5782 break;
5783 }
5784
5785 case Instruction::Trunc: {
5786 EVT TruncVT = TLI->getValueType(*DL, I->getType());
5787 unsigned TruncBitWidth = TruncVT.getSizeInBits();
5788 DemandBits.setLowBits(TruncBitWidth);
5789 break;
5790 }
5791
5792 default:
5793 return false;
5794 }
5795 }
5796
5797 uint32_t ActiveBits = DemandBits.getActiveBits();
5798 // Avoid hoisting (and (load x) 1) since it is unlikely to be folded by the
5799 // target even if isLoadExtLegal says an i1 EXTLOAD is valid. For example,
5800 // for the AArch64 target isLoadExtLegal(ZEXTLOAD, i32, i1) returns true, but
5801 // (and (load x) 1) is not matched as a single instruction, rather as a LDR
5802 // followed by an AND.
5803 // TODO: Look into removing this restriction by fixing backends to either
5804 // return false for isLoadExtLegal for i1 or have them select this pattern to
5805 // a single instruction.
5806 //
5807 // Also avoid hoisting if we didn't see any ands with the exact DemandBits
5808 // mask, since these are the only ands that will be removed by isel.
5809 if (ActiveBits <= 1 || !DemandBits.isMask(ActiveBits) ||
5810 WidestAndBits != DemandBits)
5811 return false;
5812
5813 LLVMContext &Ctx = Load->getType()->getContext();
5814 Type *TruncTy = Type::getIntNTy(Ctx, ActiveBits);
5815 EVT TruncVT = TLI->getValueType(*DL, TruncTy);
5816
5817 // Reject cases that won't be matched as extloads.
5818 if (!LoadResultVT.bitsGT(TruncVT) || !TruncVT.isRound() ||
5819 !TLI->isLoadExtLegal(ISD::ZEXTLOAD, LoadResultVT, TruncVT))
5820 return false;
5821
5822 IRBuilder<> Builder(Load->getNextNode());
5823 auto *NewAnd = dyn_cast<Instruction>(
5824 Builder.CreateAnd(Load, ConstantInt::get(Ctx, DemandBits)));
5825 // Mark this instruction as "inserted by CGP", so that other
5826 // optimizations don't touch it.
5827 InsertedInsts.insert(NewAnd);
5828
5829 // Replace all uses of load with new and (except for the use of load in the
5830 // new and itself).
5831 Load->replaceAllUsesWith(NewAnd);
5832 NewAnd->setOperand(0, Load);
5833
5834 // Remove any and instructions that are now redundant.
5835 for (auto *And : AndsToMaybeRemove)
5836 // Check that the and mask is the same as the one we decided to put on the
5837 // new and.
5838 if (cast<ConstantInt>(And->getOperand(1))->getValue() == DemandBits) {
5839 And->replaceAllUsesWith(NewAnd);
5840 if (&*CurInstIterator == And)
5841 CurInstIterator = std::next(And->getIterator());
5842 And->eraseFromParent();
5843 ++NumAndUses;
5844 }
5845
5846 ++NumAndsAdded;
5847 return true;
5848}
5849
5850/// Check if V (an operand of a select instruction) is an expensive instruction
5851/// that is only used once.
5852static bool sinkSelectOperand(const TargetTransformInfo *TTI, Value *V) {
5853 auto *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(V);
5854 // If it's safe to speculatively execute, then it should not have side
5855 // effects; therefore, it's safe to sink and possibly *not* execute.
5856 return I && I->hasOneUse() && isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute(I) &&
5857 TTI->getUserCost(I) >= TargetTransformInfo::TCC_Expensive;
5858}
5859
5860/// Returns true if a SelectInst should be turned into an explicit branch.
5861static bool isFormingBranchFromSelectProfitable(const TargetTransformInfo *TTI,
5862 const TargetLowering *TLI,
5863 SelectInst *SI) {
5864 // If even a predictable select is cheap, then a branch can't be cheaper.
5865 if (!TLI->isPredictableSelectExpensive())
5866 return false;
5867
5868 // FIXME: This should use the same heuristics as IfConversion to determine
5869 // whether a select is better represented as a branch.
5870
5871 // If metadata tells us that the select condition is obviously predictable,
5872 // then we want to replace the select with a branch.
5873 uint64_t TrueWeight, FalseWeight;
5874 if (SI->extractProfMetadata(TrueWeight, FalseWeight)) {
5875 uint64_t Max = std::max(TrueWeight, FalseWeight);
5876 uint64_t Sum = TrueWeight + FalseWeight;
5877 if (Sum != 0) {
5878 auto Probability = BranchProbability::getBranchProbability(Max, Sum);
5879 if (Probability > TLI->getPredictableBranchThreshold())
5880 return true;
5881 }
5882 }
5883
5884 CmpInst *Cmp = dyn_cast<CmpInst>(SI->getCondition());
5885
5886 // If a branch is predictable, an out-of-order CPU can avoid blocking on its
5887 // comparison condition. If the compare has more than one use, there's
5888 // probably another cmov or setcc around, so it's not worth emitting a branch.
5889 if (!Cmp || !Cmp->hasOneUse())
5890 return false;
5891
5892 // If either operand of the select is expensive and only needed on one side
5893 // of the select, we should form a branch.
5894 if (sinkSelectOperand(TTI, SI->getTrueValue()) ||
5895 sinkSelectOperand(TTI, SI->getFalseValue()))
5896 return true;
5897
5898 return false;
5899}
5900
5901/// If \p isTrue is true, return the true value of \p SI, otherwise return
5902/// false value of \p SI. If the true/false value of \p SI is defined by any
5903/// select instructions in \p Selects, look through the defining select
5904/// instruction until the true/false value is not defined in \p Selects.
5905static Value *getTrueOrFalseValue(
5906 SelectInst *SI, bool isTrue,
5907 const SmallPtrSet<const Instruction *, 2> &Selects) {
5908 Value *V = nullptr;
5909
5910 for (SelectInst *DefSI = SI; DefSI != nullptr && Selects.count(DefSI);
5911 DefSI = dyn_cast<SelectInst>(V)) {
5912 assert(DefSI->getCondition() == SI->getCondition() &&
5913 "The condition of DefSI does not match with SI");
5914 V = (isTrue ? DefSI->getTrueValue() : DefSI->getFalseValue());
5915 }
5916
5917 assert(V && "Failed to get select true/false value");
5918 return V;
5919}
5920
5921/// If we have a SelectInst that will likely profit from branch prediction,
5922/// turn it into a branch.
5923bool CodeGenPrepare::optimizeSelectInst(SelectInst *SI) {
5924 // If branch conversion isn't desirable, exit early.
5925 if (DisableSelectToBranch || OptSize || !TLI)
5926 return false;
5927
5928 // Find all consecutive select instructions that share the same condition.
5929 SmallVector<SelectInst *, 2> ASI;
5930 ASI.push_back(SI);
5931 for (BasicBlock::iterator It = ++BasicBlock::iterator(SI);
5932 It != SI->getParent()->end(); ++It) {
5933 SelectInst *I = dyn_cast<SelectInst>(&*It);
5934 if (I && SI->getCondition() == I->getCondition()) {
5935 ASI.push_back(I);
5936 } else {
5937 break;
5938 }
5939 }
5940
5941 SelectInst *LastSI = ASI.back();
5942 // Increment the current iterator to skip all the rest of select instructions
5943 // because they will be either "not lowered" or "all lowered" to branch.
5944 CurInstIterator = std::next(LastSI->getIterator());
5945
5946 bool VectorCond = !SI->getCondition()->getType()->isIntegerTy(1);
5947
5948 // Can we convert the 'select' to CF ?
5949 if (VectorCond || SI->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_unpredictable))
5950 return false;
5951
5952 TargetLowering::SelectSupportKind SelectKind;
5953 if (VectorCond)
5954 SelectKind = TargetLowering::VectorMaskSelect;
5955 else if (SI->getType()->isVectorTy())
5956 SelectKind = TargetLowering::ScalarCondVectorVal;
5957 else
5958 SelectKind = TargetLowering::ScalarValSelect;
5959
5960 if (TLI->isSelectSupported(SelectKind) &&
5961 !isFormingBranchFromSelectProfitable(TTI, TLI, SI))
5962 return false;
5963
5964 // The DominatorTree needs to be rebuilt by any consumers after this
5965 // transformation. We simply reset here rather than setting the ModifiedDT
5966 // flag to avoid restarting the function walk in runOnFunction for each
5967 // select optimized.
5968 DT.reset();
5969
5970 // Transform a sequence like this:
5971 // start:
5972 // %cmp = cmp uge i32 %a, %b
5973 // %sel = select i1 %cmp, i32 %c, i32 %d
5974 //
5975 // Into:
5976 // start:
5977 // %cmp = cmp uge i32 %a, %b
5978 // br i1 %cmp, label %select.true, label %select.false
5979 // select.true:
5980 // br label %select.end
5981 // select.false:
5982 // br label %select.end
5983 // select.end:
5984 // %sel = phi i32 [ %c, %select.true ], [ %d, %select.false ]
5985 //
5986 // In addition, we may sink instructions that produce %c or %d from
5987 // the entry block into the destination(s) of the new branch.
5988 // If the true or false blocks do not contain a sunken instruction, that
5989 // block and its branch may be optimized away. In that case, one side of the
5990 // first branch will point directly to select.end, and the corresponding PHI
5991 // predecessor block will be the start block.
5992
5993 // First, we split the block containing the select into 2 blocks.
5994 BasicBlock *StartBlock = SI->getParent();
5995 BasicBlock::iterator SplitPt = ++(BasicBlock::iterator(LastSI));
5996 BasicBlock *EndBlock = StartBlock->splitBasicBlock(SplitPt, "select.end");
5997
5998 // Delete the unconditional branch that was just created by the split.
5999 StartBlock->getTerminator()->eraseFromParent();
6000
6001 // These are the new basic blocks for the conditional branch.
6002 // At least one will become an actual new basic block.
6003 BasicBlock *TrueBlock = nullptr;
6004 BasicBlock *FalseBlock = nullptr;
6005 BranchInst *TrueBranch = nullptr;
6006 BranchInst *FalseBranch = nullptr;
6007
6008 // Sink expensive instructions into the conditional blocks to avoid executing
6009 // them speculatively.
6010 for (SelectInst *SI : ASI) {
6011 if (sinkSelectOperand(TTI, SI->getTrueValue())) {
6012 if (TrueBlock == nullptr) {
6013 TrueBlock = BasicBlock::Create(SI->getContext(), "select.true.sink",
6014 EndBlock->getParent(), EndBlock);
6015 TrueBranch = BranchInst::Create(EndBlock, TrueBlock);
6016 TrueBranch->setDebugLoc(SI->getDebugLoc());
6017 }
6018 auto *TrueInst = cast<Instruction>(SI->getTrueValue());
6019 TrueInst->moveBefore(TrueBranch);
6020 }
6021 if (sinkSelectOperand(TTI, SI->getFalseValue())) {
6022 if (FalseBlock == nullptr) {
6023 FalseBlock = BasicBlock::Create(SI->getContext(), "select.false.sink",
6024 EndBlock->getParent(), EndBlock);
6025 FalseBranch = BranchInst::Create(EndBlock, FalseBlock);
6026 FalseBranch->setDebugLoc(SI->getDebugLoc());
6027 }
6028 auto *FalseInst = cast<Instruction>(SI->getFalseValue());
6029 FalseInst->moveBefore(FalseBranch);
6030 }
6031 }
6032
6033 // If there was nothing to sink, then arbitrarily choose the 'false' side
6034 // for a new input value to the PHI.
6035 if (TrueBlock == FalseBlock) {
6036 assert(TrueBlock == nullptr &&
6037 "Unexpected basic block transform while optimizing select");
6038
6039 FalseBlock = BasicBlock::Create(SI->getContext(), "select.false",
6040 EndBlock->getParent(), EndBlock);
6041 auto *FalseBranch = BranchInst::Create(EndBlock, FalseBlock);
6042 FalseBranch->setDebugLoc(SI->getDebugLoc());
6043 }
6044
6045 // Insert the real conditional branch based on the original condition.
6046 // If we did not create a new block for one of the 'true' or 'false' paths
6047 // of the condition, it means that side of the branch goes to the end block
6048 // directly and the path originates from the start block from the point of
6049 // view of the new PHI.
6050 BasicBlock *TT, *FT;
6051 if (TrueBlock == nullptr) {
6052 TT = EndBlock;
6053 FT = FalseBlock;
6054 TrueBlock = StartBlock;
6055 } else if (FalseBlock == nullptr) {
6056 TT = TrueBlock;
6057 FT = EndBlock;
6058 FalseBlock = StartBlock;
6059 } else {
6060 TT = TrueBlock;
6061 FT = FalseBlock;
6062 }
6063 IRBuilder<>(SI).CreateCondBr(SI->getCondition(), TT, FT, SI);
6064
6065 SmallPtrSet<const Instruction *, 2> INS;
6066 INS.insert(ASI.begin(), ASI.end());
6067 // Use reverse iterator because later select may use the value of the
6068 // earlier select, and we need to propagate value through earlier select
6069 // to get the PHI operand.
6070 for (auto It = ASI.rbegin(); It != ASI.rend(); ++It) {
6071 SelectInst *SI = *It;
6072 // The select itself is replaced with a PHI Node.
6073 PHINode *PN = PHINode::Create(SI->getType(), 2, "", &EndBlock->front());
6074 PN->takeName(SI);
6075 PN->addIncoming(getTrueOrFalseValue(SI, true, INS), TrueBlock);
6076 PN->addIncoming(getTrueOrFalseValue(SI, false, INS), FalseBlock);
6077 PN->setDebugLoc(SI->getDebugLoc());
6078
6079 SI->replaceAllUsesWith(PN);
6080 SI->eraseFromParent();
6081 INS.erase(SI);
6082 ++NumSelectsExpanded;
6083 }
6084
6085 // Instruct OptimizeBlock to skip to the next block.
6086 CurInstIterator = StartBlock->end();
6087 return true;
6088}
6089
6090static bool isBroadcastShuffle(ShuffleVectorInst *SVI) {
6091 SmallVector<int, 16> Mask(SVI->getShuffleMask());
6092 int SplatElem = -1;
6093 for (unsigned i = 0; i < Mask.size(); ++i) {
6094 if (SplatElem != -1 && Mask[i] != -1 && Mask[i] != SplatElem)
6095 return false;
6096 SplatElem = Mask[i];
6097 }
6098
6099 return true;
6100}
6101
6102/// Some targets have expensive vector shifts if the lanes aren't all the same
6103/// (e.g. x86 only introduced "vpsllvd" and friends with AVX2). In these cases
6104/// it's often worth sinking a shufflevector splat down to its use so that
6105/// codegen can spot all lanes are identical.
6106bool CodeGenPrepare::optimizeShuffleVectorInst(ShuffleVectorInst *SVI) {
6107 BasicBlock *DefBB = SVI->getParent();
6108
6109 // Only do this xform if variable vector shifts are particularly expensive.
6110 if (!TLI || !TLI->isVectorShiftByScalarCheap(SVI->getType()))
6111 return false;
6112
6113 // We only expect better codegen by sinking a shuffle if we can recognise a
6114 // constant splat.
6115 if (!isBroadcastShuffle(SVI))
6116 return false;
6117
6118 // InsertedShuffles - Only insert a shuffle in each block once.
6119 DenseMap<BasicBlock*, Instruction*> InsertedShuffles;
6120
6121 bool MadeChange = false;
6122 for (User *U : SVI->users()) {
6123 Instruction *UI = cast<Instruction>(U);
6124
6125 // Figure out which BB this ext is used in.
6126 BasicBlock *UserBB = UI->getParent();
6127 if (UserBB == DefBB) continue;
6128
6129 // For now only apply this when the splat is used by a shift instruction.
6130 if (!UI->isShift()) continue;
6131
6132 // Everything checks out, sink the shuffle if the user's block doesn't
6133 // already have a copy.
6134 Instruction *&InsertedShuffle = InsertedShuffles[UserBB];
6135
6136 if (!InsertedShuffle) {
6137 BasicBlock::iterator InsertPt = UserBB->getFirstInsertionPt();
6138 assert(InsertPt != UserBB->end());
6139 InsertedShuffle =
6140 new ShuffleVectorInst(SVI->getOperand(0), SVI->getOperand(1),
6141 SVI->getOperand(2), "", &*InsertPt);
6142 }
6143
6144 UI->replaceUsesOfWith(SVI, InsertedShuffle);
6145 MadeChange = true;
6146 }
6147
6148 // If we removed all uses, nuke the shuffle.
6149 if (SVI->use_empty()) {
6150 SVI->eraseFromParent();
6151 MadeChange = true;
6152 }
6153
6154 return MadeChange;
6155}
6156
6157bool CodeGenPrepare::tryToSinkFreeOperands(Instruction *I) {
6158 // If the operands of I can be folded into a target instruction together with
6159 // I, duplicate and sink them.
6160 SmallVector<Use *, 4> OpsToSink;
6161 if (!TLI || !TLI->shouldSinkOperands(I, OpsToSink))
6162 return false;
6163
6164 // OpsToSink can contain multiple uses in a use chain (e.g.
6165 // (%u1 with %u1 = shufflevector), (%u2 with %u2 = zext %u1)). The dominating
6166 // uses must come first, which means they are sunk first, temporarily creating
6167 // invalid IR. This will be fixed once their dominated users are sunk and
6168 // updated.
6169 BasicBlock *TargetBB = I->getParent();
6170 bool Changed = false;
6171 SmallVector<Use *, 4> ToReplace;
6172 for (Use *U : OpsToSink) {
6173 auto *UI = cast<Instruction>(U->get());
6174 if (UI->getParent() == TargetBB || isa<PHINode>(UI))
6175 continue;
6176 ToReplace.push_back(U);
6177 }
6178
6179 SmallPtrSet<Instruction *, 4> MaybeDead;
6180 for (Use *U : ToReplace) {
6181 auto *UI = cast<Instruction>(U->get());
6182 Instruction *NI = UI->clone();
6183 MaybeDead.insert(UI);
6184 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Sinking " << *UI << " to user " << *I << "\n");
6185 NI->insertBefore(I);
6186 InsertedInsts.insert(NI);
6187 U->set(NI);
6188 Changed = true;
6189 }
6190
6191 // Remove instructions that are dead after sinking.
6192 for (auto *I : MaybeDead)
6193 if (!I->hasNUsesOrMore(1))
6194 I->eraseFromParent();
6195
6196 return Changed;
6197}
6198
6199bool CodeGenPrepare::optimizeSwitchInst(SwitchInst *SI) {
6200 if (!TLI || !DL)
6201 return false;
6202
6203 Value *Cond = SI->getCondition();
6204 Type *OldType = Cond->getType();
6205 LLVMContext &Context = Cond->getContext();
6206 MVT RegType = TLI->getRegisterType(Context, TLI->getValueType(*DL, OldType));
6207 unsigned RegWidth = RegType.getSizeInBits();
6208
6209 if (RegWidth <= cast<IntegerType>(OldType)->getBitWidth())
6210 return false;
6211
6212 // If the register width is greater than the type width, expand the condition
6213 // of the switch instruction and each case constant to the width of the
6214 // register. By widening the type of the switch condition, subsequent
6215 // comparisons (for case comparisons) will not need to be extended to the
6216 // preferred register width, so we will potentially eliminate N-1 extends,
6217 // where N is the number of cases in the switch.
6218 auto *NewType = Type::getIntNTy(Context, RegWidth);
6219
6220 // Zero-extend the switch condition and case constants unless the switch
6221 // condition is a function argument that is already being sign-extended.
6222 // In that case, we can avoid an unnecessary mask/extension by sign-extending
6223 // everything instead.
6224 Instruction::CastOps ExtType = Instruction::ZExt;
6225 if (auto *Arg = dyn_cast<Argument>(Cond))
6226 if (Arg->hasSExtAttr())
6227 ExtType = Instruction::SExt;
6228
6229 auto *ExtInst = CastInst::Create(ExtType, Cond, NewType);
6230 ExtInst->insertBefore(SI);
6231 ExtInst->setDebugLoc(SI->getDebugLoc());
6232 SI->setCondition(ExtInst);
6233 for (auto Case : SI->cases()) {
6234 APInt NarrowConst = Case.getCaseValue()->getValue();
6235 APInt WideConst = (ExtType == Instruction::ZExt) ?
6236 NarrowConst.zext(RegWidth) : NarrowConst.sext(RegWidth);
6237 Case.setValue(ConstantInt::get(Context, WideConst));
6238 }
6239
6240 return true;
6241}
6242
6243
6244namespace {
6245
6246/// Helper class to promote a scalar operation to a vector one.
6247/// This class is used to move downward extractelement transition.
6248/// E.g.,
6249/// a = vector_op <2 x i32>
6250/// b = extractelement <2 x i32> a, i32 0
6251/// c = scalar_op b
6252/// store c
6253///
6254/// =>
6255/// a = vector_op <2 x i32>
6256/// c = vector_op a (equivalent to scalar_op on the related lane)
6257/// * d = extractelement <2 x i32> c, i32 0
6258/// * store d
6259/// Assuming both extractelement and store can be combine, we get rid of the
6260/// transition.
6261class VectorPromoteHelper {
6262 /// DataLayout associated with the current module.
6263 const DataLayout &DL;
6264
6265 /// Used to perform some checks on the legality of vector operations.
6266 const TargetLowering &TLI;
6267
6268 /// Used to estimated the cost of the promoted chain.
6269 const TargetTransformInfo &TTI;
6270
6271 /// The transition being moved downwards.
6272 Instruction *Transition;
6273
6274 /// The sequence of instructions to be promoted.
6275 SmallVector<Instruction *, 4> InstsToBePromoted;
6276
6277 /// Cost of combining a store and an extract.
6278 unsigned StoreExtractCombineCost;
6279
6280 /// Instruction that will be combined with the transition.
6281 Instruction *CombineInst = nullptr;
6282
6283 /// The instruction that represents the current end of the transition.
6284 /// Since we are faking the promotion until we reach the end of the chain
6285 /// of computation, we need a way to get the current end of the transition.
6286 Instruction *getEndOfTransition() const {
6287 if (InstsToBePromoted.empty())
6288 return Transition;
6289 return InstsToBePromoted.back();
6290 }
6291
6292 /// Return the index of the original value in the transition.
6293 /// E.g., for "extractelement <2 x i32> c, i32 1" the original value,
6294 /// c, is at index 0.
6295 unsigned getTransitionOriginalValueIdx() const {
6296 assert(isa<ExtractElementInst>(Transition) &&
6297 "Other kind of transitions are not supported yet");
6298 return 0;
6299 }
6300
6301 /// Return the index of the index in the transition.
6302 /// E.g., for "extractelement <2 x i32> c, i32 0" the index
6303 /// is at index 1.
6304 unsigned getTransitionIdx() const {
6305 assert(isa<ExtractElementInst>(Transition) &&
6306 "Other kind of transitions are not supported yet");
6307 return 1;
6308 }
6309
6310 /// Get the type of the transition.
6311 /// This is the type of the original value.
6312 /// E.g., for "extractelement <2 x i32> c, i32 1" the type of the
6313 /// transition is <2 x i32>.
6314 Type *getTransitionType() const {
6315 return Transition->getOperand(getTransitionOriginalValueIdx())->getType();
6316 }
6317
6318 /// Promote \p ToBePromoted by moving \p Def downward through.
6319 /// I.e., we have the following sequence:
6320 /// Def = Transition <ty1> a to <ty2>
6321 /// b = ToBePromoted <ty2> Def, ...
6322 /// =>
6323 /// b = ToBePromoted <ty1> a, ...
6324 /// Def = Transition <ty1> ToBePromoted to <ty2>
6325 void promoteImpl(Instruction *ToBePromoted);
6326
6327 /// Check whether or not it is profitable to promote all the
6328 /// instructions enqueued to be promoted.
6329 bool isProfitableToPromote() {
6330 Value *ValIdx = Transition->getOperand(getTransitionOriginalValueIdx());
6331 unsigned Index = isa<ConstantInt>(ValIdx)
6332 ? cast<ConstantInt>(ValIdx)->getZExtValue()
6333 : -1;
6334 Type *PromotedType = getTransitionType();
6335
6336 StoreInst *ST = cast<StoreInst>(CombineInst);
6337 unsigned AS = ST->getPointerAddressSpace();
6338 unsigned Align = ST->getAlignment();
6339 // Check if this store is supported.
6340 if (!TLI.allowsMisalignedMemoryAccesses(
6341 TLI.getValueType(DL, ST->getValueOperand()->getType()), AS,
6342 Align)) {
6343 // If this is not supported, there is no way we can combine
6344 // the extract with the store.
6345 return false;
6346 }
6347
6348 // The scalar chain of computation has to pay for the transition
6349 // scalar to vector.
6350 // The vector chain has to account for the combining cost.
6351 uint64_t ScalarCost =
6352 TTI.getVectorInstrCost(Transition->getOpcode(), PromotedType, Index);
6353 uint64_t VectorCost = StoreExtractCombineCost;
6354 for (const auto &Inst : InstsToBePromoted) {
6355 // Compute the cost.
6356 // By construction, all instructions being promoted are arithmetic ones.
6357 // Moreover, one argument is a constant that can be viewed as a splat
6358 // constant.
6359 Value *Arg0 = Inst->getOperand(0);
6360 bool IsArg0Constant = isa<UndefValue>(Arg0) || isa<ConstantInt>(Arg0) ||
6361 isa<ConstantFP>(Arg0);
6362 TargetTransformInfo::OperandValueKind Arg0OVK =
6363 IsArg0Constant ? TargetTransformInfo::OK_UniformConstantValue
6364 : TargetTransformInfo::OK_AnyValue;
6365 TargetTransformInfo::OperandValueKind Arg1OVK =
6366 !IsArg0Constant ? TargetTransformInfo::OK_UniformConstantValue
